const Q_SEC_ENGLISH=[{"id": "sde71001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read: 'The Apprenticeship\n\nMarcus had worked in his uncle's bicycle repair shop every Saturday for two years, but he had never been allowed to touch a customer's bike without supervision. That changed on a wet Tuesday afternoon when his uncle was called away to a family emergency, leaving Marcus alone with a queue of impatient customers and a workshop full of half-finished repairs.\n\nThe first job looked simple enough: a loose chain on an old mountain bike. Marcus had watched his uncle fix dozens of these. His hands, however, seemed clumsier than usual, fumbling with the tension screws as the owner hovered nearby, checking his watch every few minutes. When the chain finally clicked back into place, Marcus felt a flush of pride that lasted exactly as long as it took to notice the brake cable he'd accidentally loosened in the process.\n\nBy the third customer, something shifted. Marcus stopped trying to remember exactly what his uncle would do and started actually looking at the bike in front of him — really looking, the way his uncle always told him to but he'd never quite understood until now. The gears weren't shifting because of a bent derailleur, not a worn cable as he'd first assumed. He fixed it in under ten minutes.\n\nHis uncle returned just as Marcus was wiping down his tools, surprised to find the workshop quieter than he'd left it and every customer gone, apparently satisfied. \"Slow day?\" his uncle asked, glancing at the empty queue. Marcus considered explaining everything that had happened, then decided against it. \"Something like that,\" he said, and went back to sweeping the floor, allowing himself a small, private smile.'\n\nWhy was Marcus left alone in the workshop?", "options": ["his uncle had gone on holiday", "his uncle was called away to a family emergency", "his uncle wanted to test him deliberately", "the shop had run out of customers"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states his uncle 'was called away to a family emergency'.", "hint": "Look at the end of the first paragraph."}, {"id": "sde71002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat went wrong with the first repair?", "options": ["Marcus fixed the wrong bike entirely", "Marcus accidentally loosened the brake cable", "the customer refused to pay", "Marcus couldn't find the right tools"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states that while fixing the chain, Marcus accidentally loosened the brake cable.", "hint": "Look at the end of the second paragraph."}, {"id": "sde71003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat caused the shift in Marcus's approach by the third customer?", "options": ["he called his uncle for help", "he started actually examining each bike properly, rather than just recalling what his uncle would do", "he gave up and sent the customer away", "he used a manual to look up each repair"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states Marcus 'stopped trying to remember exactly what his uncle would do and started actually looking at the bike in front of him'.", "hint": "Look at the start of the third paragraph for what changed in his approach."}, {"id": "sde71004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat was the actual cause of the gear problem on the third bike?", "options": ["a worn cable, as Marcus first assumed", "a bent derailleur", "a loose chain", "a flat tyre"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states the gears weren't shifting 'because of a bent derailleur, not a worn cable as he'd first assumed'.", "hint": "Look carefully — the passage first mentions Marcus's incorrect assumption, then the real cause."}, {"id": "sde71005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does Marcus decide not to tell his uncle everything that happened?", "options": ["he is too embarrassed to speak", "the passage doesn't explicitly say, but it suggests quiet pride and confidence rather than a need for approval", "he is afraid of being punished", "he doesn't remember what happened"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Marcus's 'private smile' and brief reply suggest a quiet, personal satisfaction that doesn't need his uncle's recognition to be meaningful.", "hint": "Look at how the passage describes Marcus's reaction at the very end."}, {"id": "sde71006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'fumbling' suggest about Marcus's hands in the second paragraph?", "options": ["they were moving confidently and precisely", "they were moving clumsily and with difficulty", "they were perfectly steady", "they were not moving at all"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Fumbling\" suggests clumsy, uncertain movements, which fits with the description of his hands seeming 'clumsier than usual'.", "hint": "This word describes handling something awkwardly or with difficulty."}, {"id": "sde71007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Text Structure", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of this passage?", "options": ["a character struggles, then gradually grows more capable through experience", "a character succeeds easily from the very start", "two characters have an ongoing argument", "a process is explained in a list of numbered steps"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The passage follows Marcus from early mistakes to a moment of genuine competence, reflecting gradual growth through experience.", "hint": "Think about how Marcus's confidence and skill change from the start of the passage to the end."}, {"id": "sde71008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is suggested by Marcus's uncle saying 'Slow day?' upon returning?", "options": ["he immediately suspects something went wrong", "he is unaware of everything Marcus dealt with, and assumes little happened", "he is angry at Marcus", "he already knew what Marcus did before arriving"], "answer": 1, "exp": "His uncle's casual question suggests he has no idea how much actually happened, simply noticing the empty queue and assuming a quiet day.", "hint": "Think about what 'Slow day?' implies about his uncle's awareness of events."}, {"id": "sde71009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read: 'Why Lights-Out Curfews for Phones Might Actually Help Teenagers Sleep\n\nSleep researchers have spent the last decade investigating a question many parents have asked for years: does using a phone before bed actually affect how well a teenager sleeps? A growing body of evidence suggests the answer is yes — and the reasons are more complex than simple distraction.\n\nThe most commonly cited factor is blue light, the type of light emitted by phone and tablet screens. Blue light exposure in the evening can suppress the body's production of melatonin, a hormone that signals to the brain that it's time to sleep. Even short exposure, researchers have found, can shift a person's natural sleep cycle later by 30 minutes or more.\n\nHowever, blue light is only part of the picture. Equally significant is what researchers call \"cognitive arousal\" — the mental stimulation caused by scrolling through social media, replying to messages, or watching engaging videos. Unlike reading a physical book, which tends to be calming, these activities can keep the brain alert and engaged well past the point when a person intends to fall asleep.\n\nSome schools and families have experimented with simple phone curfews — for example, requiring phones to be switched off or placed in another room an hour before bedtime. Early results from several small studies are promising, showing modest improvements in both how quickly teenagers fall asleep and how rested they report feeling the next day. Critics point out that these studies are often small and short-term, and that enforcing such curfews in practice can be difficult, particularly when teenagers use their phones as alarm clocks.\n\nWhatever the eventual policy implications, the underlying science is becoming difficult to ignore. As more research accumulates, it seems increasingly likely that the hour before bed matters far more than most teenagers — or their parents — currently assume.'\n\nAccording to the text, what does blue light exposure suppress?", "options": ["adrenaline", "melatonin", "caffeine", "serotonin"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states blue light exposure 'can suppress the body's production of melatonin'.", "hint": "Look at the second paragraph for the specific hormone mentioned."}, {"id": "sde71010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is 'cognitive arousal', according to the passage?", "options": ["a type of blue light", "the mental stimulation caused by engaging activities like scrolling or messaging", "a medical condition affecting teenagers only", "a type of sleep curfew"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage defines cognitive arousal as 'the mental stimulation caused by scrolling through social media, replying to messages, or watching engaging videos'.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for the definition given."}, {"id": "sde71011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer mention that reading a physical book 'tends to be calming'?", "options": ["to argue that books should replace all phones", "to contrast it with the more stimulating effect of phone activities", "to suggest that reading is now outdated", "to prove that phones are never useful before bed"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This comparison highlights the contrast between calming activities and the more mentally stimulating effect of typical phone use before bed.", "hint": "Think about why comparing two different activities might help make a point."}, {"id": "sde71012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat criticism do critics raise about the phone curfew studies?", "options": ["the studies cost too much money", "the studies are often small and short-term", "the studies were conducted only on adults", "the studies have been proven completely false"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states critics 'point out that these studies are often small and short-term'.", "hint": "Look at the fourth paragraph for the specific criticism mentioned."}, {"id": "sde71013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat practical difficulty does the passage mention regarding phone curfews?", "options": ["phones are too expensive to replace", "teenagers often use their phones as alarm clocks", "schools refuse to allow any phone use", "parents are not interested in trying curfews"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage notes that enforcing curfews can be difficult 'particularly when teenagers use their phones as alarm clocks'.", "hint": "Look at the end of the fourth paragraph for this specific practical issue."}, {"id": "sde71014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's overall stance by the end of the passage?", "options": ["phone curfews are completely proven and should be mandatory everywhere", "the science increasingly suggests the hour before bed matters more than most people assume", "there is no real evidence connecting phones to sleep at all", "blue light is the only factor that matters"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The final paragraph states it 'seems increasingly likely that the hour before bed matters far more than most teenagers — or their parents — currently assume', without claiming the matter is fully settled.", "hint": "Look at the final paragraph for the writer's overall conclusion."}, {"id": "sde71015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'modest' mean in the phrase 'modest improvements' in the fourth paragraph?", "options": ["extremely large", "embarrassing", "small but noticeable", "completely absent"], "answer": 2, "exp": "In this context, \"modest\" means small but still noticeable improvements, not dramatic or huge ones.", "hint": "Think about a word describing something moderate in size, not extreme in either direction."}, {"id": "sde71016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Text Structure", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the text type of this passage?", "options": ["a persuasive opinion piece with no evidence", "an informative report presenting research findings and differing perspectives", "a fictional short story", "a set of step-by-step instructions"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage presents research findings, defines key terms, and acknowledges criticism — characteristic of an informative report rather than fiction or pure persuasion.", "hint": "Think about whether the passage tells a story, gives instructions, or presents information and evidence."}, {"id": "sde71017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy might the writer have included the critics' viewpoint in the fourth paragraph?", "options": ["to completely undermine the rest of the passage", "to present a balanced view by acknowledging limitations in the research", "because the writer disagrees with everything stated earlier", "by accident, with no real purpose"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Including critics' viewpoints alongside the research findings reflects a balanced, evidence-based approach to reporting on a developing area of science.", "hint": "Think about why a writer reporting on science might want to mention limitations, not just positive findings."}, {"id": "sde71018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'apprehensive'?", "options": ["confident", "anxious", "relaxed", "indifferent"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Anxious\" means worried or nervous, similar in meaning to 'apprehensive'.", "hint": "Think of a word describing nervous anticipation about something."}, {"id": "sde71019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'meticulous'?", "options": ["careless", "careful and precise", "quick", "forgetful"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Careful and precise\" matches the meaning of 'meticulous', which describes great attention to detail.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who pays very close attention to detail."}, {"id": "sde71020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'reluctant'?", "options": ["hesitant", "willing", "unsure", "nervous"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Willing\" is the opposite of 'reluctant', which means unwilling or hesitant.", "hint": "Think of a word describing eagerness, the opposite of hesitation."}, {"id": "sde71021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'candid'?", "options": ["secretive", "honest and direct", "confused", "silent"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Honest and direct\" matches the meaning of 'candid', which describes truthful, frank speech.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone speaking very openly and truthfully."}, {"id": "sde71022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'skeptical'?", "options": ["doubtful", "trusting", "excited", "confident"], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Doubtful\" matches the meaning of 'skeptical', which describes having doubts about something.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who isn't easily convinced."}, {"id": "sde71023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'concise'?", "options": ["brief", "wordy", "clear", "simple"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Wordy\" is the opposite of 'concise', which describes speech or writing that is brief and to the point.", "hint": "Think of a word describing speech or writing that uses far more words than necessary."}, {"id": "sde71024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'diligent'?", "options": ["lazy", "hardworking", "forgetful", "careless"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Hardworking\" matches the meaning of 'diligent', which describes careful and persistent effort.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who works steadily and conscientiously."}, {"id": "sde71025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'ambiguous'?", "options": ["unclear", "confusing", "clear", "vague"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Clear\" is the opposite of 'ambiguous', which describes something open to more than one interpretation.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something with only one obvious meaning."}, {"id": "sde72001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Sentence Types", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence is a compound sentence?", "options": ["The dog barked loudly.", "Although it was raining, we went outside.", "The dog barked, and the cat ran away.", "Running quickly, she caught the bus."], "answer": 2, "exp": "A compound sentence joins two independent clauses with a coordinating conjunction (like 'and'). \"The dog barked, and the cat ran away\" contains two complete ideas joined by 'and'.", "hint": "A compound sentence has two complete ideas joined by a word like 'and', 'but', or 'or'."}, {"id": "sde72002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Sentence Types", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence is a complex sentence?", "options": ["The sun was shining.", "The sun was shining, and the birds were singing.", "Because the sun was shining, we decided to go for a walk.", "The sun shone brightly."], "answer": 2, "exp": "A complex sentence contains an independent clause and at least one dependent clause. \"Because the sun was shining\" is a dependent clause attached to the independent clause \"we decided to go for a walk\".", "hint": "Look for a sentence with a dependent clause (one that can't stand alone) joined to a main clause."}, {"id": "sde72003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Clauses", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Identify the dependent clause in this sentence: 'After the movie ended, we walked home in the rain.'", "options": ["we walked home", "in the rain", "After the movie ended", "we walked home in the rain"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"After the movie ended\" cannot stand alone as a complete sentence, making it the dependent clause.", "hint": "A dependent clause cannot stand alone as a complete sentence."}, {"id": "sde72004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Parts of Speech — Conjunctions", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which word is a coordinating conjunction?", "options": ["because", "although", "but", "since"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"But\" is one of the coordinating conjunctions (along with for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so), used to join independent clauses of equal importance.", "hint": "Remember the acronym FANBOYS: for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so."}, {"id": "sde72005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Active and Passive Voice", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses the passive voice?", "options": ["The chef cooked the meal.", "The meal was cooked by the chef.", "The chef is cooking the meal.", "The chef will cook the meal."], "answer": 1, "exp": "In the passive voice, the subject receives the action rather than performing it. \"The meal was cooked by the chef\" places the meal (the receiver of the action) as the subject.", "hint": "In passive voice, the subject receives the action instead of doing it."}, {"id": "sde72006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Punctuation — Apostrophes", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses an apostrophe to show possession?", "options": ["The dogs bone was buried.", "The dog's bone was buried.", "The dogs' bone was buried, if there is only one dog.", "The dogs's bone was buried."], "answer": 1, "exp": "For a single dog, the apostrophe goes before the 's': \"the dog's bone\".", "hint": "For a single owner, the apostrophe goes before the 's'."}, {"id": "sde72007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Punctuation — Apostrophes", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses an apostrophe for a plural possessive?", "options": ["The students' books were left on the desks.", "The student's books were left on the desks, if there are several students.", "The students books were left on the desks.", "The studentss' books were left on the desks."], "answer": 0, "exp": "For a plural noun already ending in 's' (students), the apostrophe goes after the 's': \"the students' books\".", "hint": "For a plural noun ending in 's', the apostrophe goes after the 's'."}, {"id": "sde72008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Punctuation — Semicolons", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses a semicolon correctly?", "options": ["I love reading; especially mystery novels.", "I love reading; my sister prefers watching movies.", "I love reading, my sister prefers watching movies; instead.", "I love; reading mystery novels."], "answer": 1, "exp": "A semicolon can join two related independent clauses. \"I love reading\" and \"my sister prefers watching movies\" are both complete ideas, correctly joined with a semicolon.", "hint": "A semicolon joins two complete, related sentences without needing a conjunction."}, {"id": "sde72009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Parts of Speech — Prepositions", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which word in this sentence is a preposition? 'The cat jumped over the fence.'", "options": ["cat", "jumped", "over", "fence"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Over\" shows the relationship between the cat's action and the fence, making it a preposition.", "hint": "A preposition often shows position or direction, like 'over', 'under', or 'beside'."}, {"id": "sde72010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Direct and Indirect Speech", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence is written in direct speech?", "options": ["She said that she was tired.", "She said, \"I am tired.\"", "She mentioned being tired.", "She told us she felt tired."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Direct speech uses quotation marks to show someone's exact spoken words: \"I am tired.\"", "hint": "Direct speech is shown using quotation marks around the exact words spoken."}, {"id": "sde72011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Direct and Indirect Speech", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Convert this direct speech to indirect (reported) speech: 'I am going to the shop,' said Tom.", "options": ["Tom said, \"I am going to the shop.\"", "Tom said that he was going to the shop.", "Tom is going to the shop, he said.", "Tom asked if he could go to the shop."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Indirect speech reports what was said without quotation marks, often changing the tense: \"Tom said that he was going to the shop.\"", "hint": "Indirect speech reports the meaning without using the exact quoted words or quotation marks."}, {"id": "sde72012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Clauses", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence contains a relative clause?", "options": ["The book was interesting.", "The book, which I borrowed from the library, was interesting.", "The book was on the table.", "I read the book quickly."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Which I borrowed from the library\" is a relative clause, giving extra information about 'the book'.", "hint": "A relative clause often begins with 'which', 'who', 'that', or 'whose' and gives extra information."}, {"id": "sde72013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Parts of Speech — Conjunctions", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which word correctly completes the sentence: 'Neither the teacher ___ the students were ready for the test.'", "options": ["or", "nor", "and", "but"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Neither... nor...\" is a correlative conjunction pair used to connect two negative alternatives.", "hint": "\"Neither\" is paired with a specific conjunction to express two negative alternatives."}, {"id": "sde72014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Punctuation — Commas", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses correct comma placement in a list?", "options": ["I packed shoes socks and a hat.", "I packed shoes, socks and a hat.", "I packed shoes socks, and a hat.", "I packed, shoes, socks, and a hat."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Commas separate items in a list, with the final comma before 'and' being optional (the Oxford comma): \"shoes, socks and a hat.\"", "hint": "Commas should separate each item in the list, with no comma needed right after the verb."}, {"id": "sde72015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Punctuation — Commas", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses a comma after an introductory clause?", "options": ["After the storm passed the town began to clean up.", "After the storm passed, the town began to clean up.", "After, the storm passed the town began to clean up.", "After the storm, passed the town began to clean up."], "answer": 1, "exp": "A comma should follow an introductory dependent clause, before the main clause begins: \"After the storm passed, the town began to clean up.\"", "hint": "Place the comma right after the introductory clause ends, before the main clause starts."}, {"id": "sde72016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Sentence Structure", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "What is the subject of this sentence? 'The brightly coloured kite soared above the trees.'", "options": ["brightly", "coloured", "kite", "trees"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Kite\" is the noun performing the action of soaring, making it the subject of the sentence.", "hint": "The subject is the noun performing the main action of the sentence."}, {"id": "sde72017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Grammar — Subject-Verb Agreement", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates correct subject-verb agreement?", "options": ["The list of names were posted on the board.", "The list of names was posted on the board.", "The list of names is being posted on the boards, were they.", "The lists of name was posted."], "answer": 1, "exp": "The subject is \"the list\" (singular), so the verb must also be singular: \"was posted\", even though 'names' (plural) comes between them.", "hint": "Find the true subject of the sentence — ignore the words in between that might confuse you."}, {"id": "sde72018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Parts of Speech — Adverbs", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which word in this sentence is an adverb? 'She spoke quietly during the meeting.'", "options": ["spoke", "quietly", "during", "meeting"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Quietly\" describes how she spoke, making it an adverb modifying the verb 'spoke'.", "hint": "Adverbs often describe how an action is performed, and many end in '-ly'."}, {"id": "sde72019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Punctuation — Colons", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses a colon correctly?", "options": ["I need: milk, eggs, and bread.", "I need the following items: milk, eggs, and bread.", "I need the following items, milk, eggs, and bread.", "I need: the following items milk, eggs, and bread."], "answer": 1, "exp": "A colon introduces a list after a complete independent clause: \"I need the following items: milk, eggs, and bread.\"", "hint": "A colon should come after a complete sentence, introducing a list or explanation."}, {"id": "sde72020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Punctuation — Apostrophes", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Identify the correct plural possessive form: the toys belonging to several children.", "options": ["childrens' toys", "children's toys", "childrens toys", "childrens's toys"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Children\" is already plural without an 's', so the possessive simply adds 's after it: \"children's toys\".", "hint": "\"Children\" doesn't end in 's', so the possessive follows the normal singular rule."}, {"id": "sde72021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Grammar — Modifiers", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence contains a dangling modifier (an error)?", "options": ["Running quickly, Sam caught the bus.", "Running quickly, the bus was caught by Sam.", "Sam, running quickly, caught the bus.", "Sam ran quickly and caught the bus."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Running quickly, the bus was caught by Sam\" incorrectly suggests the bus was running, since the modifier should describe Sam, not the bus.", "hint": "Check who or what the opening phrase is actually describing — it should match the subject right after the comma."}, {"id": "sde72022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Parts of Speech — Pronouns", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which word in this sentence is a pronoun? 'Maria finished the book and gave it to him.'", "options": ["finished", "book", "it", "gave"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"It\" stands in for the noun 'the book', making it a pronoun. (\"Him\" is also a pronoun in this sentence, but only 'it' was offered as an option here.)", "hint": "A pronoun takes the place of a noun, like 'it', 'her', 'him', or 'they'."}, {"id": "sde72023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Grammar — Verb Tense", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence is in the past perfect tense?", "options": ["She had finished her homework before dinner.", "She finishes her homework before dinner.", "She will finish her homework before dinner.", "She is finishing her homework before dinner."], "answer": 0, "exp": "Past perfect tense uses 'had' plus a past participle to show an action completed before another past action: \"She had finished her homework before dinner.\"", "hint": "Past perfect tense uses the word 'had' along with a past participle."}, {"id": "sde72024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Punctuation — Quotation Marks", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses quotation marks for a quote within a quote?", "options": ["She said, \"My favourite line is 'to be or not to be'.\"", "She said, 'My favourite line is \"to be or not to be\".'", "She said \"My favourite line is to be or not to be\".", "She said, \"My favourite line is to be or not to be.\""], "answer": 0, "exp": "When a quote appears inside another quote, single quotation marks are used for the inner quote, within double quotation marks for the outer quote.", "hint": "Use single quotation marks for the quote inside the main double-quoted speech."}, {"id": "sde72025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Commonly Confused Words", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses the correct form of 'fewer' or 'less'?", "options": ["There are less students in this class than last year.", "There are fewer students in this class than last year.", "There is fewer student in this class.", "There are less student in this class."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Fewer\" is used for countable nouns (like 'students'), while 'less' is used for uncountable quantities.", "hint": "Use 'fewer' for things you can count individually, like people or objects."}, {"id": "sde73001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'reluctant'?", "options": ["eager", "hesitant", "confident", "relaxed"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Hesitant\" matches the meaning of 'reluctant', describing unwillingness or hesitation.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who doesn't want to do something."}, {"id": "sde73002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'abundant'?", "options": ["plentiful", "scarce", "huge", "common"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Scarce\" is the opposite of 'abundant', which means existing in large quantities.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something in short supply."}, {"id": "sde73003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Word Origins — Prefixes", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "The prefix 'bi-' usually relates to which number?", "options": ["one", "two", "three", "ten"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The prefix 'bi-' relates to the number two, as in 'bicycle' (two wheels) or 'bilingual' (two languages).", "hint": "Think of words like 'bicycle' or 'bilingual'."}, {"id": "sde73004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Word Origins — Roots", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "The root word 'chron' relates to which concept?", "options": ["colour", "time", "sound", "light"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The root 'chron' relates to time, as in 'chronological' (in time order) or 'chronicle' (a record over time).", "hint": "Think of words like 'chronological' or 'synchronise'."}, {"id": "sde73005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'persuade'?", "options": ["confuse", "convince", "ignore", "forbid"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Convince\" matches the meaning of 'persuade', meaning to cause someone to believe or do something through reasoning.", "hint": "Think of a word describing getting someone to agree with you."}, {"id": "sde73006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "A writer asks, 'Do we really want our city's history paved over for another car park?' What persuasive technique is this an example of?", "options": ["a statistic", "a rhetorical question", "an anecdote", "a direct command"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A rhetorical question is asked to make a point or provoke thought, rather than to genuinely seek an answer.", "hint": "This technique poses a question that isn't really expecting a direct answer."}, {"id": "sde73007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "A persuasive text states: 'Studies show that 78% of residents oppose the new development.' What technique is this?", "options": ["repetition", "a statistic", "emotive language", "a rhetorical question"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Citing a specific number ('78%') is an example of using a statistic to support an argument.", "hint": "This technique uses a specific number to add weight to an argument."}, {"id": "sde73008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "A persuasive text repeats the phrase 'We deserve better' three times across a paragraph. What technique is this?", "options": ["repetition", "alliteration", "a statistic", "a counter-argument"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Repeating the same phrase multiple times is an example of repetition, used to reinforce a key message.", "hint": "This technique involves saying the same thing more than once for emphasis."}, {"id": "sde73009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which phrase is the best example of emotive language in a persuasive text?", "options": ["The council reviewed the proposal.", "Families will be devastated if this heartless decision goes ahead.", "The meeting was held on Tuesday.", "The proposal received 40 votes."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Devastated\" and \"heartless\" are emotionally charged words designed to provoke a strong feeling in the reader, which is the purpose of emotive language.", "hint": "Look for the option using strong, feeling-based words rather than neutral, factual language."}, {"id": "sde73010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'inevitable'?", "options": ["avoidable", "unlikely", "unavoidable", "surprising"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Unavoidable\" matches the meaning of 'inevitable', describing something certain to happen.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that cannot be prevented."}, {"id": "sde73011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Word Origins — Prefixes", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "The prefix 'tri-' usually relates to which number?", "options": ["two", "three", "four", "five"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The prefix 'tri-' relates to the number three, as in 'triangle' (three angles) or 'tricycle' (three wheels).", "hint": "Think of words like 'triangle' or 'tricycle'."}, {"id": "sde73012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Word Origins — Roots", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "The root word 'photo' relates to which concept?", "options": ["sound", "light", "water", "movement"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The root 'photo' relates to light, as in 'photograph' (recorded using light) or 'photosynthesis' (using light energy).", "hint": "Think of words like 'photograph' or 'photosynthesis'."}, {"id": "sde73013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'transparent' (when describing honesty)?", "options": ["open", "secretive", "clear", "obvious"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Secretive\" is the opposite of 'transparent' in this context, which describes being open and honest.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who hides information rather than sharing it openly."}, {"id": "sde73014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "A persuasive speaker says, 'Imagine your own child going without food tonight.' What technique is being used here?", "options": ["a statistic", "an appeal to emotion", "a counter-argument", "alliteration"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Asking the audience to imagine a personal, emotional scenario is designed to create an emotional connection, which is an appeal to emotion.", "hint": "This technique tries to make the audience personally feel the issue, rather than just think about facts."}, {"id": "sde73015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'scrutinise'?", "options": ["ignore", "examine closely", "approve", "summarise"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Examine closely\" matches the meaning of 'scrutinise', which means to inspect something carefully.", "hint": "Think of a word describing looking at something very carefully and critically."}, {"id": "sde73016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "A writer acknowledges 'Some argue this policy is too expensive' before responding with reasons why it's still worthwhile. What technique is this?", "options": ["addressing a counter-argument", "using alliteration", "repetition", "a rhetorical question"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Raising and then responding to an opposing view is the technique of addressing a counter-argument, which can make a writer's position seem more reasonable.", "hint": "This technique involves acknowledging an opposing view before responding to it."}, {"id": "sde73017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Word Origins — Suffixes", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "The suffix '-phobia' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["love", "fear", "knowledge", "speed"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The suffix '-phobia' relates to fear, as in 'arachnophobia' (fear of spiders) or 'claustrophobia' (fear of confined spaces).", "hint": "Think of words like 'arachnophobia' or 'claustrophobia'."}, {"id": "sde73018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'futile'?", "options": ["successful", "pointless", "urgent", "simple"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Pointless\" matches the meaning of 'futile', which describes something incapable of achieving any result.", "hint": "Think of a word describing an effort that has no chance of success."}, {"id": "sde73019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "A slogan reads: 'Save our streets, save our future.' What technique combines repetition with structure here?", "options": ["onomatopoeia", "parallelism (repeated sentence structure)", "a simile", "a direct quote"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Repeating the same sentence structure ('Save our ___') creates parallelism, making the slogan more memorable and rhythmic.", "hint": "This technique repeats a grammatical pattern, not just a single word."}, {"id": "sde73020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'verbose'?", "options": ["wordy", "concise", "detailed", "loud"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Concise\" is the opposite of 'verbose', which describes using more words than necessary.", "hint": "Think of a word describing speech or writing that is brief and to the point."}, {"id": "sde73021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Word Origins — Roots", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "The root word 'aud' relates to which concept?", "options": ["sight", "hearing", "taste", "touch"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The root 'aud' relates to hearing, as in 'audience' (those who listen) or 'audible' (able to be heard).", "hint": "Think of words like 'audience' or 'audible'."}, {"id": "sde73022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'pragmatic'?", "options": ["impractical", "idealistic", "practical and realistic", "emotional"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Practical and realistic\" matches the meaning of 'pragmatic', describing a sensible, results-focused approach.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who deals with things in a sensible, realistic way."}, {"id": "sde73023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "A persuasive text uses the line, 'Don't just sit there — act now!' What technique is this an example of?", "options": ["a direct command (imperative)", "a simile", "alliteration", "a counter-argument"], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Act now\" is a direct command (an imperative sentence), urging the audience to take immediate action.", "hint": "This technique uses a command form, directly telling the audience what to do."}, {"id": "sde73024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Word Origins — Prefixes", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "The prefix 'auto-' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["self", "many", "far", "fast"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The prefix 'auto-' relates to self, as in 'autobiography' (a story of one's own life) or 'automatic' (operating by itself).", "hint": "Think of words like 'autobiography' or 'automatic'."}, {"id": "sde73025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'ambivalent'?", "options": ["certain", "having mixed feelings", "angry", "excited"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Having mixed feelings\" matches the meaning of 'ambivalent', describing uncertainty between two viewpoints or feelings.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone torn between two different feelings about something."}, {"id": "sde74001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read: 'Why Every School Needs a Later Start Time\n\nIt's 7:15 am, and somewhere across the country, a tired teenager is being shaken awake for school, despite having fallen asleep only six hours earlier. This scene repeats itself in millions of households every single morning — and it's a problem we have the power to fix.\n\nThe science on this issue is no longer in dispute. Adolescent brains undergo a natural shift during the teenage years, delaying the release of melatonin until later in the evening. This isn't laziness, and it isn't a lifestyle choice — it's basic biology. Forcing teenagers to wake before 7 am, when their bodies are biologically still in deep sleep, is the equivalent of waking an adult at 4 am every single day.\n\nCritics will say that later start times simply shift the problem, pushing bedtimes later instead of solving anything. But multiple large-scale studies tell a different story: when schools delay start times by even 30 to 60 minutes, average sleep duration increases, not decreases. Students aren't staying up later to compensate — they're finally getting the sleep their changing bodies actually need.\n\nThe benefits extend far beyond simply feeling less tired. Schools that have shifted to later start times report measurable improvements in student attendance, mood, and even road safety, with fewer car accidents among newly licensed teenage drivers during the early morning commute. Academic performance, too, shows modest but consistent improvement, particularly in first-period classes.\n\nOf course, change is never without complications. Bus schedules need adjusting. After-school sports and part-time jobs may need to shift. Working parents may need to rethink their morning routines. These are genuine, practical concerns — but they are logistical puzzles to be solved, not reasons to ignore an entire body of medical evidence. We would never tell a diabetic patient to ignore their condition because adjusting their diet is inconvenient. We shouldn't treat adolescent sleep biology any differently.'\n\nWhat is the writer's main argument?", "options": ["that teenagers are simply lazy and need more discipline", "that schools should start later because of biological changes in teenage sleep patterns", "that all schools should remove early morning classes entirely", "that parents are responsible for teenagers' tiredness"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer argues throughout that school start times should be later, specifically because of biological changes affecting teenage sleep, not due to laziness or poor choices.", "hint": "Look at the opening and the explanation of melatonin for the writer's central claim."}, {"id": "sde74002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer compare an early teenage start time to 'waking an adult at 4 am'?", "options": ["to make a literal, scientific comparison", "to use exaggeration that helps readers feel how disruptive this schedule is for teenagers", "to suggest adults should also wake up earlier", "to provide an unrelated fact"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This comparison is a persuasive technique that helps readers emotionally grasp how disruptive an early start feels for a teenager's altered sleep cycle, even though it's not a literal scientific equivalence.", "hint": "Think about why comparing this to an adult's experience might help readers understand the teenager's perspective."}, {"id": "sde74003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's response to the criticism that later start times just shift bedtimes later?", "options": ["the writer agrees and offers no response", "studies show sleep duration actually increases, rather than students simply staying up later", "the writer ignores this criticism entirely", "the writer admits the criticism is completely valid"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer directly counters this criticism by citing studies showing 'average sleep duration increases, not decreases' when start times are delayed.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for how the writer directly responds to this specific criticism."}, {"id": "sde74004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich of these is presented as a benefit of later school start times, according to the passage?", "options": ["increased road accidents", "reduced road accidents among new teen drivers", "reduced school attendance", "worse academic performance"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states schools with later start times report 'fewer car accidents among newly licensed teenage drivers during the early morning commute'.", "hint": "Look at the fourth paragraph for the specific safety benefit mentioned."}, {"id": "sde74005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer compare this issue to telling 'a diabetic patient to ignore their condition'?", "options": ["to argue that diabetes and sleep are the same medical condition", "to argue that practical inconvenience shouldn't override clear medical evidence", "to confuse the reader with an unrelated topic", "to suggest that schools should ignore all health issues"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This analogy supports the writer's argument that practical difficulties (like bus schedules) shouldn't be used as an excuse to dismiss clear biological evidence, just as we wouldn't dismiss a medical condition for being inconvenient to manage.", "hint": "Think about how this comparison reinforces the writer's point about evidence versus convenience."}, {"id": "sde74006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich practical concerns does the writer acknowledge in the final paragraph?", "options": ["bus schedules, after-school activities, and parents' routines", "only bus schedules", "only academic performance", "none — the writer claims there are no real concerns"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The final paragraph lists several practical concerns: bus schedules, after-school sports and jobs, and parents' morning routines.", "hint": "Look at the final paragraph for the list of practical complications mentioned."}, {"id": "sde74007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'dispute' mean in the second paragraph?", "options": ["agreement", "disagreement or debate", "celebration", "explanation"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"In dispute\" means under disagreement or debate. The writer states the science is 'no longer in dispute', meaning it's now widely agreed upon.", "hint": "Think about what it means for something to still be argued over, versus settled."}, {"id": "sde74008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Interpreting Mood", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall tone of this passage?", "options": ["uncertain and apologetic", "confident and persuasive", "humorous and light-hearted", "angry and aggressive"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer makes firm claims, cites evidence, and directly counters criticism throughout, reflecting a confident and persuasive tone.", "hint": "Think about how directly and firmly the writer states their position throughout the passage."}, {"id": "sde74009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read: 'The Last Bell\n\nThe corridor empties in a rush of noise,\nbackpacks swinging, voices rising loud,\nfive years of mornings spent in these same halls\ncollapsing now into one final crowd.\n\nI used to count the days until this one,\nmark them off in red across the wall,\nand now the number's gone to nothing, none,\nand I'm not sure I wanted it at all.\n\nMr. Hendricks waves from his classroom door,\nthe one who failed me once, then let me try again,\nand somewhere in that quiet second chance\nI learned more than he likely meant to teach me then.\n\nThe bell that rings is just a bell, of course,\na small mechanical, unremarkable sound,\nbut something in my chest goes strangely still\nas if the whole world paused to look around.\n\nI thought I'd run the moment I was free.\nInstead I'm standing here, in no great hurry,\nwatching five years fold themselves away\ninto a hallway I won't see in any worry —\n\nexcept I will. I know that even now.\nSome doors don't close as cleanly as they seem.\nI'll think of this same hallway, oddly enough,\nlong after it's reduced to just a dream.'\n\nWhat event is the speaker describing in this poem?", "options": ["the first day of school", "a fire drill", "the final day at a school the speaker is leaving", "a school holiday"], "answer": 2, "exp": "The poem describes 'the last bell' and 'five years' collapsing into one final crowd, indicating this is the speaker's final day at this school.", "hint": "Look at the title and the references to 'five years' and 'final' throughout the poem."}, {"id": "sde74010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Interpreting Mood", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nIn the second stanza, what does the speaker reveal about their feelings towards this day?", "options": ["they had always dreaded this day", "they had been counting down to it eagerly, but now feel surprisingly uncertain", "they feel nothing at all", "they are angry about leaving"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The speaker describes counting down the days, but now says \"I'm not sure I wanted it at all\", revealing unexpected uncertainty.", "hint": "Look for the contrast between how the speaker felt before and how they feel now."}, {"id": "sde74011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the third stanza reveal about Mr. Hendricks?", "options": ["he was a strict teacher who never helped anyone", "he gave the speaker a second chance after failing them once, leading to an unexpected lesson", "he is leaving the school as well", "he never spoke to the speaker"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem describes Mr. Hendricks as 'the one who failed me once, then let me try again', and the speaker learned something valuable from that experience.", "hint": "Look at the third stanza for the specific detail about this teacher's role in the speaker's experience."}, {"id": "sde74012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat literary device is used in the phrase 'a small mechanical, unremarkable sound'?", "options": ["simile", "description that downplays the bell's true emotional significance", "onomatopoeia", "rhyme only"], "answer": 1, "exp": "By describing the bell as 'small' and 'unremarkable', the poet creates an ironic contrast with the deep emotional impact it actually has on the speaker, shown in the next lines.", "hint": "Think about why the poet downplays the bell's sound right before describing such a strong physical reaction to it."}, {"id": "sde74013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the phrase 'something in my chest goes strangely still' suggest about the speaker?", "options": ["they are having a medical emergency", "they feel a sudden, quiet emotional reaction to the moment", "they are bored", "they are about to fall asleep"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This physical description reflects a quiet, internal emotional reaction — a moment of stillness and reflection rather than a literal physical problem.", "hint": "Think about how physical sensations are often used in poetry to express emotion."}, {"id": "sde74014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the final stanza suggest about the speaker's true feelings about leaving?", "options": ["they will forget about the school completely and immediately", "they suspect they will continue thinking about this place long after leaving", "they regret every moment spent at the school", "they are excited to never think about it again"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The lines \"I'll think of this same hallway, oddly enough, long after it's reduced to just a dream\" suggest the speaker expects this place to stay meaningful long after leaving.", "hint": "Look at the very last stanza for what the speaker predicts about their future feelings."}, {"id": "sde74015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhich best describes the rhyme pattern used within each four-line stanza?", "options": ["every line rhymes with every other line", "the first and third lines rhyme, and the second and fourth lines rhyme (an ABAB-style pattern)", "there is no rhyme at all", "only the first two lines rhyme"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Looking at each stanza, the first and third lines share an end rhyme, and the second and fourth lines share a different end rhyme, forming an ABAB-style pattern.", "hint": "Check the end words of lines 1 and 3, then lines 2 and 4, in any stanza."}, {"id": "sde74016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat is the overall theme of this poem?", "options": ["the excitement of starting a new school", "the bittersweet, complicated feelings of leaving somewhere familiar", "the importance of arriving to school on time", "a description of a typical school day"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem explores mixed, complex emotions — eagerness to leave alongside unexpected nostalgia — reflecting the bittersweet nature of moving on from somewhere familiar.", "hint": "Think about how the speaker's feelings shift and mix throughout the poem, rather than being simply happy or sad."}, {"id": "sde74017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Figurative Language", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Which sentence contains a simile?", "options": ["The wind howled through the trees.", "Her smile was as bright as the morning sun.", "The car was fast.", "He ran quickly to the door."], "answer": 1, "exp": "A simile compares two things using 'like' or 'as'. \"As bright as the morning sun\" compares her smile to the sun using 'as'.", "hint": "A simile uses the words 'like' or 'as' to compare two different things."}, {"id": "sde74018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Figurative Language", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Which sentence contains a metaphor?", "options": ["The classroom was a zoo by the end of the day.", "The classroom was noisy.", "The classroom was like a zoo.", "The classroom had many students."], "answer": 0, "exp": "A metaphor states that one thing IS another, without using 'like' or 'as'. \"The classroom was a zoo\" directly equates the two, rather than comparing them.", "hint": "A metaphor says something IS something else, without using 'like' or 'as'."}, {"id": "sde74019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Figurative Language", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Which phrase is an example of personification?", "options": ["The dog ran fast.", "The wind whispered secrets through the trees.", "The car was red.", "The book was heavy."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Personification gives human qualities to non-human things. \"The wind whispered secrets\" gives the wind a human ability (whispering).", "hint": "Personification gives human actions or qualities to something non-human."}, {"id": "sde74020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Figurative Language", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Which phrase is an example of alliteration?", "options": ["The big brown bear blundered by.", "The cat sat on the mat.", "She ran to the shop.", "The sky was blue today."], "answer": 0, "exp": "Alliteration repeats the same starting consonant sound in nearby words. \"Big brown bear blundered\" repeats the 'b' sound.", "hint": "Alliteration repeats the same beginning sound across several nearby words."}, {"id": "sde74021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Figurative Language", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Which phrase is an example of onomatopoeia?", "options": ["The bee buzzed past my ear.", "The bee flew past my ear.", "The bee was yellow and black.", "The bee landed on a flower."], "answer": 0, "exp": "Onomatopoeia uses words that imitate sounds. \"Buzzed\" imitates the actual sound a bee makes.", "hint": "Onomatopoeia is a word that sounds like the noise it describes."}, {"id": "sde74022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Figurative Language", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "What is hyperbole?", "options": ["a quiet, calm tone", "an extreme exaggeration not meant to be taken literally", "a type of rhyme", "a factual statement"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Hyperbole is deliberate, extreme exaggeration used for emphasis or effect, such as saying \"I've told you a million times.\"", "hint": "This device involves exaggerating something far beyond what's literally true, for effect."}, {"id": "sde74023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Figurative Language", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "Which sentence is an example of hyperbole?", "options": ["I'm a little hungry.", "I could eat a horse, I'm so hungry.", "I would like a sandwich.", "I haven't eaten since breakfast."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"I could eat a horse\" is an extreme exaggeration not meant literally, used to emphasise how hungry the speaker feels.", "hint": "Look for the option that exaggerates far beyond what's realistically true."}, {"id": "sde74024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "What effect does repeating a consonant sound (alliteration) usually have on a piece of writing?", "options": ["it makes the writing harder to understand", "it can create rhythm and draw attention to a phrase", "it always makes writing sound sad", "it has no real effect on the reader"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Alliteration often creates rhythm and can make a phrase more memorable or emphatic by drawing the reader's attention to it.", "hint": "Think about why advertising slogans and poems often use repeated sounds."}, {"id": "sde74025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "7", "topic": "Poetry Terms", "difficulty": "medium", "style": "standard", "paper": "G7-E4", "q": "In poetry, what is a 'stanza'?", "options": ["a single word", "a group of lines forming a unit, similar to a paragraph in prose", "the title of the poem", "the rhyme scheme only"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A stanza is a group of lines grouped together within a poem, functioning similarly to a paragraph in prose writing.", "hint": "Think about how a poem's lines are grouped into sections, similar to paragraphs."}, {"id": "sde81001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read: 'The Inheritance\n\nAunt Ruth's house had been empty for three months before anyone worked up the courage to sort through it, and even then, it was only because the real estate agent kept calling about the sale. Priya volunteered, partly out of genuine affection for her great-aunt and partly to escape a family group chat that had become unbearable with arguments over who should get what.\n\nThe house smelled exactly as she remembered — old books, lavender, something faintly like burnt toast that Priya suspected was just the smell of the ancient stove. She'd expected the sorting to take an afternoon. It took four days, not because there was so much to go through, but because every drawer seemed to contain something that stopped her mid-task: photographs of relatives she'd never met, letters in handwriting too elegant to belong to anyone she knew personally, a recipe card stained with what might have been forty years of the same spilled ingredient.\n\nIt was in the bottom drawer of an unremarkable writing desk that Priya found the journal. Aunt Ruth had apparently kept one consistently from age nineteen until just a few years before her death — decades of entries, some only a single line, others sprawling across multiple pages. Priya hadn't intended to read more than a few entries. She ended up sitting on the dusty floor for three hours, utterly unaware of the cramping in her legs.\n\nWhat struck her most wasn't any single revelation, though there were a few surprising ones. It was the accumulation — watching a person's entire adult life unfold in fragments, contradictions intact, certainties from one decade quietly abandoned in the next. Ruth at twenty-five had been furious about something Priya now understood, decades later, to be almost trivial. Ruth at sixty had written, with startling clarity, about regrets she'd apparently spent thirty years avoiding. By the final entry, dated just two years before her death, she sounded, if anything, at peace — amused, even, by her younger selves.\n\nPriya didn't take much from the house in the end. A few photographs, the recipe card, and the journal, which she has not yet finished reading, three months later. She tells herself this is because she's been busy. She suspects, somewhere beneath that excuse, it's actually because finishing it will mean Aunt Ruth is more thoroughly gone than the empty house already made her feel.'\n\nWhy did Priya volunteer to sort through her aunt's house?", "options": ["she needed the money from selling items", "out of genuine affection for her aunt, and partly to escape a difficult family group chat", "her parents forced her to do it", "she had no other reason given in the text"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states she volunteered 'partly out of genuine affection for her great-aunt and partly to escape a family group chat that had become unbearable'.", "hint": "Look at the first paragraph for both reasons given."}, {"id": "sde81002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy did the sorting process take four days instead of an afternoon?", "options": ["there was an overwhelming amount of furniture to move", "every drawer contained something that stopped her, even though there wasn't actually that much to go through", "she kept getting interrupted by phone calls", "the house was too large to search quickly"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage explicitly states it wasn't because there was 'so much to go through', but because items kept stopping her mid-task emotionally.", "hint": "Look at the second paragraph for the specific reason given for the delay."}, {"id": "sde81003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the phrase 'utterly unaware of the cramping in her legs' suggest about Priya while reading the journal?", "options": ["she had fallen asleep", "she was so absorbed in reading that she lost track of physical discomfort", "she was in serious pain", "she didn't enjoy reading the journal at all"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This detail suggests Priya was so deeply absorbed in the journal that she didn't notice the physical discomfort of sitting still for so long.", "hint": "Think about what it means to be so focused on something that you stop noticing physical sensations."}, {"id": "sde81004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat change does the passage describe in Aunt Ruth between her twenties and her final years?", "options": ["she became angrier and more bitter over time", "she moved from youthful certainty and frustration toward a sense of peace and even amusement", "she completely forgot her younger experiences", "there is no real change described"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage contrasts Ruth's youthful fury over something now seen as trivial with her later, peaceful, even amused reflection in her final journal entry.", "hint": "Compare the description of Ruth at twenty-five with the description of her final journal entry."}, {"id": "sde81005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy hasn't Priya finished reading the journal, according to the final paragraph?", "options": ["she lost the journal", "she claims she's been busy, but suspects the real reason is that finishing it would make her aunt's death feel more final", "she didn't find the journal interesting", "she gave the journal away to another relative"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states her stated excuse is being busy, but suggests the deeper reason is an unwillingness to confront the finality of her aunt's death.", "hint": "Look at the very last sentence for the deeper, unstated reason suggested."}, {"id": "sde81006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'accumulation' mean in the fourth paragraph?", "options": ["a single, dramatic event", "the gradual gathering or build-up of many things over time", "a sudden loss of something", "a type of furniture"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Accumulation\" refers to the gradual gathering of many small things over time — in this case, the build-up of journal entries across decades.", "hint": "Think about something building up gradually, bit by bit, rather than happening all at once."}, {"id": "sde81007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Text Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of this passage?", "options": ["a character discovers an object that leads to a deeper emotional reflection on a relative's life", "a straightforward set of instructions for sorting a house", "an argument for and against keeping family possessions", "a comedic story with no serious themes"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The passage follows Priya's discovery of the journal and her resulting reflection on her aunt's life and her own feelings about loss.", "hint": "Think about how the passage moves from a physical task (sorting the house) to something more emotional."}, {"id": "sde81008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is suggested by Ruth's final journal entry being described as showing she was 'amused, even, by her younger selves'?", "options": ["Ruth had forgotten her younger years entirely", "Ruth had gained a sense of perspective and gentle humour about her own past", "Ruth regretted her entire life", "Ruth was confused in her final years"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Being 'amused' by her younger selves suggests Ruth had gained enough distance and perspective to look back on her past with gentle humour rather than regret or confusion.", "hint": "Think about what it means to look back on your past self with amusement, rather than anger or sadness."}, {"id": "sde81009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read: 'Should Schools Ban Energy Drinks on Campus?\n\nWalk through the halls of many secondary schools today, and you'll likely spot at least one brightly coloured energy drink can poking out of a student's bag. What was once a niche product marketed to extreme athletes has become a normalised part of teenage life, and a growing number of schools are now grappling with whether to ban them outright.\n\nThe case for banning these drinks rests largely on health concerns. A single can of many popular energy drinks contains caffeine levels comparable to two or three cups of coffee, alongside significant amounts of sugar. Paediatric health experts have raised concerns about the effects of this combination on developing adolescent bodies, citing potential impacts on heart rate, sleep patterns, and anxiety levels. Some students, researchers note, are consuming multiple cans per day — a pattern far removed from the occasional treat these products are often marketed as.\n\nOpponents of a ban raise a different set of concerns, focused less on the drinks themselves and more on the precedent such bans might set. If schools begin banning specific food and drink products based on health concerns, where exactly does that line get drawn? Sugary soft drinks, some heavily processed snack foods, and even certain sports drinks could arguably fall under similar scrutiny. Critics also point out that determined students will simply consume these drinks before arriving at school or immediately after leaving, undermining the practical impact of any on-campus ban.\n\nA middle-ground approach, adopted by a number of schools, involves restricting sales on school premises while stopping short of an outright ban on bringing drinks from home. This allows schools to avoid directly profiting from a product they consider unhealthy, while sidestepping some of the enforcement and consistency concerns raised by critics of a full ban.\n\nUltimately, the debate reflects a broader, recurring tension in school policy: balancing genuine concern for student wellbeing against the practical limits of what a school can realistically control once students leave its gates each afternoon.'\n\nAccording to the passage, what health concern is associated with energy drinks?", "options": ["they contain too much protein", "high caffeine and sugar levels affecting heart rate, sleep, and anxiety", "they cause permanent memory loss", "they are too expensive for most families"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states concerns about 'effects of this combination on developing adolescent bodies, citing potential impacts on heart rate, sleep patterns, and anxiety levels'.", "hint": "Look at the second paragraph for the specific health concerns listed."}, {"id": "sde81010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat concern do opponents of a ban raise about where 'the line gets drawn'?", "options": ["they worry that banning one product could lead to questions about banning many other similar products", "they believe energy drinks are completely harmless", "they think schools have no right to make any rules at all", "they argue energy drinks should be mandatory in schools"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The passage states critics worry about where the line would be drawn, noting that 'sugary soft drinks, some heavily processed snack foods, and even certain sports drinks could arguably fall under similar scrutiny'.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for the specific concern about consistency in banning products."}, {"id": "sde81011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the practical criticism made about banning energy drinks specifically on school campuses?", "options": ["students would simply switch to coffee instead", "determined students could just consume the drinks before or after school, limiting the ban's actual impact", "schools cannot legally enforce any food rules", "the drinks would become more popular if banned"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage notes that critics point out 'determined students will simply consume these drinks before arriving at school or immediately after leaving'.", "hint": "Look at the end of the third paragraph for this specific practical criticism."}, {"id": "sde81012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the 'middle-ground approach' described in the fourth paragraph?", "options": ["banning all sugary drinks and snacks", "restricting on-campus sales while still allowing students to bring drinks from home", "requiring parental permission for all drinks", "completely banning all drinks from school grounds"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage describes this approach as 'restricting sales on school premises while stopping short of an outright ban on bringing drinks from home'.", "hint": "Look at the fourth paragraph for the specific details of this compromise approach."}, {"id": "sde81013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the overall purpose of this passage?", "options": ["to persuade readers that energy drinks should definitely be banned", "to persuade readers that energy drinks should never be restricted", "to present multiple perspectives on a genuinely debated policy question", "to provide step-by-step instructions for writing a school policy"], "answer": 2, "exp": "The passage presents arguments both for and against a ban, along with a compromise approach, rather than arguing strongly for one single position.", "hint": "Think about whether the passage takes a strong single side, or presents multiple viewpoints fairly."}, {"id": "sde81014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'precedent' mean in the third paragraph?", "options": ["an example or decision that influences future similar situations", "a type of energy drink ingredient", "a school's daily schedule", "a legal requirement with no flexibility"], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Precedent\" refers to a decision or example that could influence how similar situations or decisions are handled in the future.", "hint": "Think about a decision made now that could set an example affecting future decisions on similar issues."}, {"id": "sde81015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the final paragraph's main point?", "options": ["the debate is simple and easily resolved", "the debate reflects a genuine, ongoing tension between student wellbeing and practical limits on what schools can control", "schools should give up trying to manage this issue entirely", "energy drinks are entirely the responsibility of parents, not schools"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The final paragraph describes this as 'a broader, recurring tension... balancing genuine concern for student wellbeing against the practical limits of what a school can realistically control'.", "hint": "Look at the very last paragraph for the writer's summary of the underlying tension in this debate."}, {"id": "sde81016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Text Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich text type best describes this passage?", "options": ["a personal narrative", "a balanced informative/discussion text exploring multiple perspectives", "a strict set of school rules", "a poem"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage presents factual information and multiple perspectives on a genuine debate, characteristic of a balanced discussion or informative text.", "hint": "Think about whether this text tells a personal story, gives instructions, or explores different sides of an issue."}, {"id": "sde81017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'niche' (as in a 'niche product')?", "options": ["mainstream", "specialised or limited to a particular group", "worthless", "expensive"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Specialised or limited to a particular group\" matches the meaning of 'niche', describing something appealing to a small, specific audience.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something aimed at a small, specific group rather than everyone."}, {"id": "sde81018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'normalised'?", "options": ["common", "unusual or unaccepted", "popular", "widespread"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Unusual or unaccepted\" is the opposite of 'normalised', which describes something that has become standard or widely accepted.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that has NOT become accepted as standard."}, {"id": "sde81019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'grappling' (as in 'grappling with a decision')?", "options": ["ignoring", "struggling to deal with", "celebrating", "avoiding entirely"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Struggling to deal with\" matches the meaning of 'grappling', describing wrestling with a difficult issue.", "hint": "Think of a word describing wrestling mentally with a tough problem."}, {"id": "sde81020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'sidestepping' (as in 'sidestepping a problem')?", "options": ["confronting directly", "avoiding cleverly", "solving completely", "ignoring rudely"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Avoiding cleverly\" matches the meaning of 'sidestepping', describing skilfully avoiding a difficulty.", "hint": "Think of a word describing cleverly moving around an obstacle rather than facing it head-on."}, {"id": "sde81021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'unremarkable'?", "options": ["ordinary", "plain", "extraordinary", "forgettable"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Extraordinary\" is the opposite of 'unremarkable', which describes something not worth noticing or commenting on.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something very noticeable and impressive, the opposite of plain or ordinary."}, {"id": "sde81022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'startling' (as in 'startling clarity')?", "options": ["boring", "strikingly surprising", "gentle", "slow"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Strikingly surprising\" matches the meaning of 'startling', which describes something that causes sudden surprise.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that gives you a sudden jolt of surprise."}, {"id": "sde81023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'trivial'?", "options": ["extremely important", "unimportant or minor", "dangerous", "confusing"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Unimportant or minor\" matches the meaning of 'trivial', describing something of little significance.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something not worth worrying about."}, {"id": "sde81024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'genuine' (as in 'genuine affection')?", "options": ["sincere", "real", "fake", "honest"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Fake\" is the opposite of 'genuine', which describes something authentic and real.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that only pretends to be real."}, {"id": "sde81025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'recurring' (as in a 'recurring tension')?", "options": ["happening only once", "happening again and again", "completely resolved", "forgotten"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Happening again and again\" matches the meaning of 'recurring', describing something that keeps reappearing over time.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that keeps coming back repeatedly."}, {"id": "sde82001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Mood", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses the subjunctive mood correctly?", "options": ["If I was rich, I would travel the world.", "If I were rich, I would travel the world.", "If I am rich, I would travel the world.", "If I will be rich, I would travel the world."], "answer": 1, "exp": "The subjunctive mood uses 'were' (not 'was') to describe hypothetical or unreal situations: \"If I were rich...\"", "hint": "For hypothetical situations starting with 'if', the correct form is 'were', not 'was'."}, {"id": "sde82002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Active and Passive Voice", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates correct use of the passive voice?", "options": ["The committee approved the proposal.", "The proposal was approved by the committee.", "The committee is approving the proposal.", "The committee will approve the proposal."], "answer": 1, "exp": "In the passive voice, the subject receives the action. \"The proposal was approved by the committee\" places the proposal (the receiver of the action) as the subject.", "hint": "In passive voice, the subject receives the action rather than performing it."}, {"id": "sde82003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Clauses", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Identify the type of clause underlined in this sentence: 'The author, who won several awards, spoke at the conference.'", "options": ["independent clause", "relative (adjective) clause", "adverbial clause", "noun clause"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Who won several awards\" is a relative clause, giving extra information about the noun 'the author'.", "hint": "This type of clause typically begins with 'who', 'which', or 'that', describing a noun."}, {"id": "sde82004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Clauses", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Identify the type of clause in this sentence: 'Whoever finishes first will receive a prize.'", "options": ["adjective clause", "adverbial clause", "noun clause acting as the subject", "independent clause only"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Whoever finishes first\" functions as the subject of the sentence, acting as a noun clause.", "hint": "Think about what role this clause is playing in the sentence — is it acting like a noun, describing something, or modifying a verb?"}, {"id": "sde82005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Clauses", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence contains an adverbial clause?", "options": ["The book, which I borrowed, was excellent.", "Whatever you decide is fine with me.", "Although it was raining, the match continued.", "The dog that barked loudly ran away."], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Although it was raining\" is an adverbial clause, providing information about the circumstances of the main clause (the match continuing).", "hint": "This type of clause often begins with words like 'although', 'because', 'when', or 'if', modifying the main clause."}, {"id": "sde82006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Punctuation — Colons", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses a colon correctly to introduce an explanation?", "options": ["She had one goal: to win the championship.", "She had one goal, to win: the championship.", "She had: one goal to win the championship.", "She had one goal to win, the championship."], "answer": 0, "exp": "A colon can introduce an explanation or elaboration after a complete clause: \"She had one goal: to win the championship.\"", "hint": "The colon should follow a complete independent clause, introducing what comes next."}, {"id": "sde82007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Punctuation — Dashes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses a dash to add an aside or interruption?", "options": ["The plan — which seemed simple at first — quickly fell apart.", "The plan, which seemed simple — at first quickly fell apart.", "The plan which seemed — simple at first, quickly fell apart.", "The — plan seemed simple at first quickly fell apart."], "answer": 0, "exp": "Dashes can be used to set off an aside or additional comment within a sentence, similar to brackets: \"The plan — which seemed simple at first — quickly fell apart.\"", "hint": "Dashes should surround the extra information as a clear, complete interruption."}, {"id": "sde82008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Parts of Speech — Conjunctions", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which word in this sentence is a subordinating conjunction? 'We stayed inside because it was raining.'", "options": ["stayed", "inside", "because", "raining"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Because\" introduces a dependent clause explaining the reason for the main clause, making it a subordinating conjunction.", "hint": "This word introduces a reason and connects a dependent clause to the main clause."}, {"id": "sde82009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Direct and Indirect Speech", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly converts direct speech into reported (indirect) speech? Direct: 'I will finish the project tomorrow,' said Maya.", "options": ["Maya said, \"I will finish the project tomorrow.\"", "Maya said that she would finish the project the next day.", "Maya said I will finish the project tomorrow.", "Maya asked if she would finish the project tomorrow."], "answer": 1, "exp": "In reported speech, 'will' often changes to 'would', 'I' changes to 'she', and 'tomorrow' may change to 'the next day': \"Maya said that she would finish the project the next day.\"", "hint": "Indirect speech often shifts the tense back and changes pronouns and time references."}, {"id": "sde82010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Modifiers", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates a misplaced modifier (an error)?", "options": ["Walking to school, Liam saw a rainbow.", "Liam saw a rainbow walking to school.", "Liam, walking to school, saw a rainbow.", "While walking to school, Liam saw a rainbow."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Liam saw a rainbow walking to school\" incorrectly suggests the rainbow was walking to school, since the modifier is placed too far from the word it should describe (Liam).", "hint": "Check whether the modifying phrase is placed close to the word it's actually describing."}, {"id": "sde82011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Parallel Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses parallel structure correctly?", "options": ["She likes hiking, swimming, and to read.", "She likes hiking, swimming, and reading.", "She likes to hike, swimming, and reading.", "She likes hiking, to swim, and reading."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Parallel structure requires items in a list to use the same grammatical form: \"hiking, swimming, and reading\" all use the '-ing' form consistently.", "hint": "Check that every item in the list uses the same grammatical form, such as all '-ing' words."}, {"id": "sde82012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Who vs Whom", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses 'who' versus 'whom'?", "options": ["Who did you give the book to?", "Whom did you give the book to?", "Whom gave the book to you?", "Who's book did you give away?"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Whom\" is correct here because it is the object of the verb 'give' (you gave the book TO whom), while 'who' is used for subjects.", "hint": "Use 'whom' when the word is the object of the verb or preposition, not the one performing the action."}, {"id": "sde82013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Verb Tense", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence is written in the past progressive (continuous) tense?", "options": ["She walked to school.", "She was walking to school when it started to rain.", "She walks to school every day.", "She will walk to school tomorrow."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Past progressive tense uses 'was/were' plus a present participle (-ing) to show an ongoing past action: \"She was walking to school...\"", "hint": "This tense uses 'was' or 'were' combined with an '-ing' verb form."}, {"id": "sde82014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Punctuation — Ellipses", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses an ellipsis to show an omission or pause?", "options": ["I was going to say something, but... never mind.", "I was going... to say something, but never mind...", "I was... going to say... something but never mind.", "I was going to say, something but never mind..."], "answer": 0, "exp": "An ellipsis (three dots) can show a pause or trailing off in thought: \"...but... never mind.\" placed naturally where the thought is interrupted.", "hint": "The ellipsis should be placed exactly where the thought trails off or pauses, not scattered randomly."}, {"id": "sde82015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Punctuation — Commas", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates correct comma usage with a non-restrictive (non-essential) clause?", "options": ["My brother who lives in Sydney is visiting next week.", "My brother, who lives in Sydney, is visiting next week.", "My brother who, lives in Sydney is visiting, next week.", "My brother lives, in Sydney who, is visiting next week."], "answer": 1, "exp": "A non-restrictive clause (extra, non-essential information) should be set off with commas on both sides: \"My brother, who lives in Sydney, is visiting next week.\"", "hint": "Non-essential extra information should be enclosed by commas on both sides."}, {"id": "sde82016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Gerunds", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which word in this sentence functions as a gerund? 'Swimming is her favourite hobby.'", "options": ["is", "her", "favourite", "Swimming"], "answer": 3, "exp": "\"Swimming\" functions as a noun here (the subject of the sentence), making it a gerund — a verb form ending in '-ing' used as a noun.", "hint": "A gerund is a verb form ending in '-ing' that acts as a noun in the sentence."}, {"id": "sde82017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Verb Tense", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses the present perfect tense correctly?", "options": ["I have visited Paris three times.", "I visit Paris three times.", "I am visiting Paris three times.", "I will have visit Paris three times."], "answer": 0, "exp": "Present perfect tense uses 'have/has' plus a past participle to describe an action that happened at an unspecified time in the past, often relevant to the present: \"I have visited Paris three times.\"", "hint": "This tense uses 'have' or 'has' combined with a past participle."}, {"id": "sde82018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Subject-Verb Agreement", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly demonstrates subject-verb agreement with a collective noun?", "options": ["The team are celebrating their win.", "The team is celebrating its win.", "The team is celebrating their win.", "The teams is celebrating its win."], "answer": 1, "exp": "In Australian English, collective nouns like 'team' are typically treated as singular, taking a singular verb ('is') and singular pronoun ('its').", "hint": "Collective nouns describing a single group are usually treated as singular in formal writing."}, {"id": "sde82019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Clauses", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence contains a noun clause functioning as the object of the verb?", "options": ["I believe that he is telling the truth.", "The man who called is my uncle.", "She left because she was tired.", "Running quickly, she caught the bus."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"That he is telling the truth\" functions as the object of the verb 'believe', making it a noun clause.", "hint": "Look for a clause acting as the thing being believed, said, or known — functioning like a noun."}, {"id": "sde82020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Punctuation — Semicolons", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of a semicolon to separate items in a complex list?", "options": ["I have lived in Sydney, Australia; Auckland, New Zealand; and Suva, Fiji.", "I have lived in Sydney; Australia, Auckland; New Zealand, and Suva; Fiji.", "I have lived in, Sydney Australia; Auckland New Zealand; and Suva Fiji.", "I have lived in Sydney, Australia, Auckland, New Zealand, and Suva, Fiji; only."], "answer": 0, "exp": "When list items themselves contain commas, semicolons can separate the larger items clearly: \"Sydney, Australia; Auckland, New Zealand; and Suva, Fiji.\"", "hint": "Use semicolons to separate list items that already contain commas within them."}, {"id": "sde82021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Verb Tense", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses the future perfect tense?", "options": ["By next year, I will have graduated from university.", "By next year, I graduate from university.", "By next year, I am graduating from university.", "By next year, I will graduate from university."], "answer": 0, "exp": "Future perfect tense uses 'will have' plus a past participle to describe an action that will be completed before a specific point in the future: \"I will have graduated...\"", "hint": "This tense uses 'will have' combined with a past participle, showing completion before a future point."}, {"id": "sde82022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Punctuation — Comma Splices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence avoids a comma splice (an error joining two independent clauses with only a comma)?", "options": ["I was tired, I went to bed early.", "I was tired; I went to bed early.", "I was tired I went to bed early.", "I was, tired, I went, to bed, early."], "answer": 1, "exp": "A semicolon (or a coordinating conjunction) correctly joins two independent clauses, avoiding the comma splice error of joining them with only a comma.", "hint": "A comma alone cannot join two complete sentences — use a semicolon, full stop, or conjunction instead."}, {"id": "sde82023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Commonly Confused Words", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses 'its' and \"it's\" correctly?", "options": ["Its a beautiful day, and the dog wagged it's tail.", "It's a beautiful day, and the dog wagged its tail.", "Its a beautiful day, and the dog wagged its tail.", "It's a beautiful day, and the dog wagged it's tail."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"It's\" (a contraction of 'it is') correctly starts the sentence, while \"its\" (showing possession, no apostrophe) correctly describes the dog's tail.", "hint": "\"It's\" means 'it is'; \"its\" shows something belongs to 'it', with no apostrophe."}, {"id": "sde82024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Participial Phrases", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates correct use of a participial phrase?", "options": ["Exhausted from the long hike, the hikers collapsed onto their sleeping bags.", "The hikers, exhausted from the long, hike collapsed onto their sleeping bags.", "Exhausted, from the long hike the hikers collapsed onto, their sleeping bags.", "The hikers collapsed exhausted, from the long hike onto their sleeping bags."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Exhausted from the long hike\" is a participial phrase correctly placed at the start, clearly modifying 'the hikers' who follow it.", "hint": "A participial phrase should be placed clearly next to the noun it describes, usually at the start or end of a sentence."}, {"id": "sde82025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Grammar — Appositives", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses an appositive (a noun phrase that renames another noun)?", "options": ["My teacher, Mrs Chen, assigned extra homework.", "My teacher Mrs Chen, assigned, extra homework.", "My, teacher Mrs Chen assigned extra homework.", "My teacher Mrs, Chen assigned extra, homework."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Mrs Chen\" is an appositive renaming 'my teacher', correctly set off with commas on both sides: \"My teacher, Mrs Chen, assigned extra homework.\"", "hint": "An appositive renames the noun before it and should be set off with commas on both sides."}, {"id": "sde83001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'pragmatic'?", "options": ["idealistic", "sensible and practical", "emotional", "careless"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Sensible and practical\" matches the meaning of 'pragmatic', describing a realistic, results-focused approach.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who deals with problems in a realistic, sensible way."}, {"id": "sde83002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'redundant'?", "options": ["unnecessary", "essential", "repetitive", "excessive"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Essential\" is the opposite of 'redundant', which describes something no longer needed because it's unnecessary or excessive.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something absolutely necessary, the opposite of unneeded."}, {"id": "sde83003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Word Origins — Roots", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "The root word 'mal-' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["good", "bad", "large", "small"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The root 'mal-' relates to something bad or wrong, as in 'malfunction' (to function badly) or 'malnutrition' (poor nutrition).", "hint": "Think of words like 'malfunction' or 'malicious'."}, {"id": "sde83004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Word Origins — Suffixes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "The suffix '-cracy' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["government or rule", "speed", "colour", "sound"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The suffix '-cracy' relates to government or rule, as in 'democracy' (rule by the people) or 'autocracy' (rule by one person).", "hint": "Think of words like 'democracy' or 'aristocracy'."}, {"id": "sde83005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "A speaker uses the phrase 'Let us rise, let us fight, let us win' in a speech. What persuasive technique combines repetition with a building intensity here?", "options": ["a tricolon (a group of three parallel phrases)", "onomatopoeia", "a simile", "a counter-argument"], "answer": 0, "exp": "A tricolon uses three parallel phrases in succession, often building intensity, as seen in \"let us rise, let us fight, let us win\".", "hint": "Count how many similar phrases are grouped together here, building toward a climax."}, {"id": "sde83006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'cynical'?", "options": ["hopeful", "distrustful of others' motives", "generous", "naive"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Distrustful of others' motives\" matches the meaning of 'cynical', describing a sceptical view of people's sincerity.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who doubts that people's actions are genuinely well-intentioned."}, {"id": "sde83007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "A writer states, 'Every parent who truly cares about their child's future will support this policy.' What persuasive (and potentially flawed) technique is this?", "options": ["a statistic", "a false dilemma, implying only one reasonable position exists", "alliteration", "a direct quote"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This statement implies that disagreeing means not caring about your child, creating a false dilemma that unfairly narrows the options to just two extremes.", "hint": "Think about how this statement unfairly suggests there's only one 'caring' position, with no room for reasonable disagreement."}, {"id": "sde83008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'vindicate'?", "options": ["to accuse falsely", "to clear of blame or justify", "to confuse", "to ignore"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"To clear of blame or justify\" matches the meaning of 'vindicate', which means to show that someone or something was right or justified.", "hint": "Think of a word describing proving that someone was right all along, after being doubted."}, {"id": "sde83009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Word Origins — Prefixes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "The prefix 'omni-' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["none", "all or everywhere", "one", "far away"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The prefix 'omni-' relates to 'all' or 'everywhere', as in 'omnivore' (eats all types of food) or 'omnipresent' (present everywhere).", "hint": "Think of words like 'omnivore' or 'omnipotent'."}, {"id": "sde83010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'benevolent'?", "options": ["kind", "generous", "malevolent", "helpful"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Malevolent\" is the opposite of 'benevolent', which describes a kind, well-meaning disposition.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone with harmful or ill intentions, the opposite of kindness."}, {"id": "sde83011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "A politician says, 'My opponent wants to bankrupt this country' without addressing the actual details of their opponent's policy. What technique is this?", "options": ["a straw man argument, misrepresenting the opponent's actual position", "a statistic", "an appeal to authority", "onomatopoeia"], "answer": 0, "exp": "A straw man argument misrepresents or exaggerates an opponent's position to make it easier to attack, rather than engaging with their actual policy.", "hint": "Think about whether this statement accurately represents the opponent's real position, or distorts it to seem worse."}, {"id": "sde83012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'eloquent'?", "options": ["clumsy with words", "fluent and persuasive in speech or writing", "silent", "confused"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Fluent and persuasive in speech or writing\" matches the meaning of 'eloquent', describing skilful, expressive communication.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who speaks or writes with great skill and persuasiveness."}, {"id": "sde83013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "A persuasive text claims, 'Renowned scientists agree this approach is best' without naming any specific scientist or study. What technique is this an example of?", "options": ["a vague appeal to authority", "a rhetorical question", "repetition", "a counter-argument"], "answer": 0, "exp": "This is a vague appeal to authority, referencing unnamed experts to add credibility without providing any specific, checkable evidence.", "hint": "Think about whether this claim provides any specific, checkable evidence, or just a vague reference to experts."}, {"id": "sde83014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Word Origins — Roots", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "The root word 'dict' relates to which concept?", "options": ["speaking or saying", "seeing", "hearing", "moving"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The root 'dict' relates to speaking or saying, as in 'dictate' (to speak aloud for someone to write down) or 'predict' (to say beforehand).", "hint": "Think of words like 'dictionary' or 'predict'."}, {"id": "sde83015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'ubiquitous'?", "options": ["rare", "present everywhere", "hidden", "dangerous"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Present everywhere\" matches the meaning of 'ubiquitous', describing something found absolutely everywhere.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something you seem to see absolutely everywhere you look."}, {"id": "sde83016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "A speaker repeatedly raises their voice and uses urgent language about a 'crisis' to discourage careful, calm analysis of an issue. What technique is this most closely associated with?", "options": ["fear-based persuasion (appeal to fear)", "a logical syllogism", "an objective summary", "a neutral comparison"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Using urgent, alarming language to provoke fear and discourage calm analysis is a recognised persuasive technique known as an appeal to fear.", "hint": "Think about the emotional reaction this technique is designed to provoke in the audience."}, {"id": "sde83017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'meticulous'?", "options": ["careful", "precise", "careless", "thorough"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Careless\" is the opposite of 'meticulous', which describes great attention to detail and precision.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who pays very little attention to detail."}, {"id": "sde83018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Word Origins — Suffixes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "The suffix '-ology' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["the study of a subject", "the size of something", "a type of disease only", "a measurement of time"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The suffix '-ology' relates to the study of a subject, as in 'biology' (the study of living things) or 'geology' (the study of the Earth).", "hint": "Think of words like 'biology' or 'psychology'."}, {"id": "sde83019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'conviction' (as in 'spoke with conviction')?", "options": ["confusion", "firm belief or certainty", "hesitation", "apology"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Firm belief or certainty\" matches the meaning of 'conviction' in this context, describing speaking with strong, confident belief.", "hint": "Think of a word describing speaking with strong, unwavering confidence in your own beliefs."}, {"id": "sde83020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "A writer compares a complex tax policy to 'a recipe with too many confusing ingredients' to help readers understand it. What technique is this?", "options": ["an analogy", "a statistic", "an appeal to fear", "onomatopoeia"], "answer": 0, "exp": "An analogy compares something unfamiliar (a tax policy) to something familiar (a recipe), helping readers understand a complex idea more easily.", "hint": "This technique compares something complicated to something simple and familiar, to aid understanding."}, {"id": "sde83021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'arbitrary'?", "options": ["carefully planned", "based on random choice rather than reason", "extremely rare", "completely fair"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Based on random choice rather than reason\" matches the meaning of 'arbitrary', describing a decision made without clear logical basis.", "hint": "Think of a word describing a decision made on a whim, rather than careful reasoning."}, {"id": "sde83022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Word Origins — Prefixes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "The prefix 'inter-' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["between or among", "above", "below", "after"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The prefix 'inter-' relates to 'between' or 'among', as in 'international' (between nations) or 'interact' (to act between/among people).", "hint": "Think of words like 'international' or 'interact'."}, {"id": "sde83023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'concur'?", "options": ["agree", "disagree", "decide", "explain"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Disagree\" is the opposite of 'concur', which means to agree with an opinion or decision.", "hint": "Think of a word describing the opposite of agreeing with someone."}, {"id": "sde83024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "A persuasive speech ends with the line, 'The time for talk is over. The time for action is now.' What technique is being used here?", "options": ["a logical fallacy only", "an antithesis (contrasting two ideas in a balanced structure)", "an irrelevant statistic", "a direct quote from research"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This is an antithesis, contrasting two ideas ('talk' versus 'action') in a balanced grammatical structure for persuasive effect.", "hint": "Think about how this line balances two contrasting ideas using similar sentence structure."}, {"id": "sde83025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'tenuous' (as in a 'tenuous connection')?", "options": ["extremely strong", "weak or flimsy", "completely certain", "obvious"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Weak or flimsy\" matches the meaning of 'tenuous', describing something only loosely or weakly connected.", "hint": "Think of a word describing a connection that is very weak or easily broken."}, {"id": "sde84001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read: 'The Disappearing Languages\n\nOf the roughly 7,000 languages spoken around the world today, linguists estimate that nearly half are at risk of disappearing entirely within the next century. Some have only a handful of fluent speakers remaining, often elderly, with no younger generation learning to speak them fluently in turn.\n\nThe causes of language loss are varied, but a common pattern emerges: as smaller communities are drawn into larger economic and social systems, children increasingly grow up speaking the dominant regional or national language, finding fewer practical reasons to learn their grandparents' language fluently. Schools, media, and employment opportunities overwhelmingly favour dominant languages, creating powerful incentives that smaller languages simply cannot compete with on practical grounds alone.\n\nWhy does this matter, beyond a vague sense of cultural loss? Linguists argue that each language encodes unique ways of categorising the world — distinct grammatical structures, specialised vocabulary for local plants, animals, and weather patterns, and culturally specific concepts that don't translate neatly into other languages. When a language disappears, this entire framework for understanding the world disappears with it, not simply a collection of words that could, in theory, be translated elsewhere.\n\nEfforts to document and revive endangered languages have grown substantially in recent decades. Linguists now race to record fluent elderly speakers before knowledge is lost entirely, while some communities have established immersion schools specifically aimed at raising new generations of fluent speakers. Hawaiian and Māori are often cited as partial success stories, having seen meaningful revival after periods of serious decline, though both remain considerably less widely spoken than they once were.\n\nThese efforts face real obstacles, however. Documentation alone cannot replace genuine, everyday fluency, and revival programs require sustained funding, community commitment, and time — resources not every endangered language community can access. Whether these efforts can meaningfully slow the broader, global pattern of language loss remains, even among optimistic linguists, a genuinely open question.'\n\nWhat proportion of the world's languages are estimated to be at risk of disappearing within the next century?", "options": ["a small fraction", "nearly half", "almost all of them", "only languages with no written form"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states linguists estimate that 'nearly half are at risk of disappearing entirely within the next century'.", "hint": "Look at the first paragraph for the specific proportion mentioned."}, {"id": "sde84002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nAccording to the passage, why do children in many communities increasingly grow up not speaking their grandparents' language fluently?", "options": ["they are forbidden from learning it", "dominant languages offer stronger practical incentives through schools, media, and employment", "they find the language too difficult to pronounce", "grandparents refuse to teach them"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states that 'schools, media, and employment opportunities overwhelmingly favour dominant languages, creating powerful incentives that smaller languages simply cannot compete with'.", "hint": "Look at the second paragraph for the specific practical reasons given."}, {"id": "sde84003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nAccording to linguists quoted in the passage, why does losing a language matter beyond a 'vague sense of cultural loss'?", "options": ["it only affects tourism revenue", "each language encodes a unique way of categorising and understanding the world", "languages have no real practical value at all", "it only matters for written literature"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states that linguists argue 'each language encodes unique ways of categorising the world', which is lost along with the language itself.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for the deeper argument made about why language loss matters."}, {"id": "sde84004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat are Hawaiian and Māori described as examples of in the fourth paragraph?", "options": ["languages that have completely disappeared", "languages that have never been at risk", "partial revival success stories, despite remaining less widely spoken than before", "languages spoken only by linguists"], "answer": 2, "exp": "The passage describes them as 'partial success stories, having seen meaningful revival after periods of serious decline, though both remain considerably less widely spoken than they once were'.", "hint": "Look at the fourth paragraph for the specific, balanced description given of these two languages."}, {"id": "sde84005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat obstacles to language revival are mentioned in the final paragraph?", "options": ["a lack of interest from linguists", "documentation alone cannot replace genuine fluency, and programs require funding, commitment, and time", "governments actively prevent all revival efforts", "there are no real obstacles mentioned"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states that 'documentation alone cannot replace genuine, everyday fluency, and revival programs require sustained funding, community commitment, and time'.", "hint": "Look at the final paragraph for the specific obstacles described."}, {"id": "sde84006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'encodes' mean in the third paragraph?", "options": ["destroys completely", "contains or represents in a particular structured form", "translates directly", "ignores entirely"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Encodes\" means to contain or represent something in a particular structured form — in this case, a language containing unique ways of understanding the world.", "hint": "Think about how information can be built into or represented within a system."}, {"id": "sde84007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Interpreting Mood", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the writer's overall tone regarding the future of endangered languages?", "options": ["entirely optimistic, with no concerns raised at all", "balanced, acknowledging both genuine revival efforts and real ongoing challenges", "completely pessimistic, suggesting nothing can be done", "dismissive of the entire issue as unimportant"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage acknowledges genuine revival efforts and partial successes, while also honestly noting 'real obstacles' and describing the overall outcome as 'a genuinely open question'.", "hint": "Look at how the passage balances hopeful examples with honest acknowledgment of difficulties."}, {"id": "sde84008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the main purpose of this passage?", "options": ["to persuade readers that only Hawaiian and Māori deserve government funding", "to inform readers about the causes, significance, and challenges of language loss and revival", "to provide a step-by-step guide to learning an endangered language", "to argue that language loss has no real consequences"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage provides balanced factual information about why languages disappear, why this matters, and the challenges and partial successes of revival efforts.", "hint": "Think about whether this passage is mainly informing, instructing, or persuading toward one narrow conclusion."}, {"id": "sde84009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read: 'Migration\n\nEvery autumn, my grandmother says,\nthe birds outside her window simply know —\nno map unfolded across a kitchen table,\nno compass needle trembling north to go.\n\nI think of her at twenty-three, one suitcase,\na language she half-knew folded in her mouth,\narriving somewhere colder than she'd pictured,\nfurther from whatever she once called south.\n\nDid she know, the way the swallows seem to know,\nsome certainty pulling at an inner thread?\nOr was it simpler — closer to just hoping,\na single step before the next instead.\n\nForty years on, she watches autumn gather\nthe same birds rising over the same grey roofs,\nand says, again, that they simply know the way,\nas if she'd half-forgotten her own proof —\n\nthat knowing, mostly, comes after the arriving,\nstitched together backward, made to seem\nlike something always certain, always simple,\nthe kind of story only distance lets you dream.'\n\nWhat does the speaker's grandmother claim about the birds in the first stanza?", "options": ["that they get lost every year", "that they simply know where to go, without any tools to guide them", "that they are guided by a kitchen map", "that they never actually migrate"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem states the grandmother believes the birds 'simply know' the way, with 'no map' and 'no compass'.", "hint": "Look at the first stanza for what the grandmother believes about the birds' navigation."}, {"id": "sde84010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat event from the grandmother's past does the second stanza describe?", "options": ["a holiday she took for fun", "her migration/move to a new country as a young woman, with only one suitcase", "her wedding day", "a dream she once had"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The second stanza describes her 'at twenty-three, one suitcase' arriving 'somewhere colder than she'd pictured', suggesting a significant migration to a new place.", "hint": "Look at the details about age, the single suitcase, and arriving somewhere unfamiliar and cold."}, {"id": "sde84011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nIn the third stanza, what question does the speaker raise about the grandmother's original journey?", "options": ["whether she regrets the journey", "whether she knew where she was going with certainty, or was simply hoping and taking it one step at a time", "whether she ever returned home", "whether she travelled alone or with others"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The speaker wonders whether the grandmother had 'some certainty pulling at an inner thread' like the birds, or whether 'it was simpler — closer to just hoping'.", "hint": "Look at the third stanza for the specific contrast the speaker considers."}, {"id": "sde84012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the final stanza suggest about how we understand our own past decisions?", "options": ["our past decisions are always perfectly clear at the time we make them", "understanding or 'knowing' often comes only afterward, reshaped by hindsight into something that feels more certain than it was", "memory is always completely accurate", "the grandmother regrets her entire journey"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The final stanza suggests \"knowing, mostly, comes after the arriving, stitched together backward\", implying our sense of certainty about past decisions is often constructed in hindsight.", "hint": "Look at the final stanza for what the poem suggests about how 'knowing' is actually formed, looking back."}, {"id": "sde84013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat is the effect of comparing the grandmother's migration to the birds' migration throughout the poem?", "options": ["it suggests her journey was meaningless", "it draws a parallel between instinctive natural behaviour and a deeply uncertain, very human decision, questioning whether her journey was as 'instinctive' as it now seems", "it proves that humans and birds migrate for identical reasons", "it has no real purpose in the poem"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This comparison invites the reader to question whether the grandmother's journey was truly as instinctive and certain as the birds' migration seems, or whether that certainty was only added in hindsight.", "hint": "Think about why comparing a human decision to animal instinct might raise an interesting question, rather than a simple, exact comparison."}, {"id": "sde84014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat literary device is used in the phrase 'a language she half-knew folded in her mouth'?", "options": ["a literal description with no figurative meaning", "a metaphor, describing an unfamiliar language as something physically folded inside her", "onomatopoeia", "alliteration only"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This metaphor describes the unfamiliar language as something physically 'folded' inside her mouth, capturing the awkward, compact, half-formed nature of speaking a language she didn't yet fully know.", "hint": "Think about whether a language can literally be 'folded', or whether this is a figurative description."}, {"id": "sde84015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhich best describes the overall theme of this poem?", "options": ["the simple joy of watching birds migrate each year", "the way certainty and meaning in difficult decisions are often only constructed afterward, through the distance of time and memory", "the importance of owning a good suitcase when travelling", "a factual account of bird migration patterns"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem explores how a sense of certainty about difficult past decisions (like migration) is often only created in hindsight, reshaped by memory and distance.", "hint": "Think about the connection the poem draws between the birds' instinct and the human experience of looking back on a difficult decision."}, {"id": "sde84016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Evaluating Evidence", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhich phrase from the poem best supports the idea that the grandmother's journey involved genuine uncertainty, not pure instinct?", "options": ["\"the birds outside her window simply know\"", "\"a single step before the next instead\"", "\"the same birds rising over the same grey roofs\"", "\"no map unfolded across a kitchen table\""], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"A single step before the next instead\" suggests a tentative, uncertain process of moving forward without full certainty, contrasting with the birds' instinctive knowing.", "hint": "Look for the phrase describing a cautious, step-by-step process, rather than confident, instinctive certainty."}, {"id": "sde84017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Figurative Language", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "What is an extended metaphor?", "options": ["a single brief comparison used once", "a metaphor that is developed and continued across multiple lines or an entire piece of writing", "a comparison using 'like' or 'as'", "a metaphor that only appears in poetry titles"], "answer": 1, "exp": "An extended metaphor is developed and continued across multiple lines, or even an entire poem, rather than appearing as a single brief comparison.", "hint": "Think about a metaphor that keeps being referenced and developed throughout a piece, not just mentioned once."}, {"id": "sde84018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Figurative Language", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Which of these is an example of irony?", "options": ["A fire station burns down.", "A dog barks loudly at night.", "Rain falls during a storm.", "A student studies for a test."], "answer": 0, "exp": "It is ironic for a fire station — a place meant to prevent and fight fires — to itself burn down, creating a contrast between expectation and reality.", "hint": "Irony often involves a surprising contrast between what is expected and what actually happens."}, {"id": "sde84019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary and Meaning", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "What is the term for the implied or suggested meaning of a word, beyond its literal dictionary definition?", "options": ["denotation", "connotation", "alliteration", "onomatopoeia"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Connotation refers to the implied or emotional meaning associated with a word, beyond its literal dictionary definition (denotation).", "hint": "This term describes the feelings or ideas a word suggests, beyond its strict definition."}, {"id": "sde84020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Vocabulary and Meaning", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Which word would have a more negative connotation than 'frugal', despite a similar literal meaning?", "options": ["thrifty", "economical", "stingy", "careful"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Stingy\" carries a more negative connotation than 'frugal', even though both relate to being careful with money.", "hint": "Think about which word makes someone sound unpleasantly unwilling to spend, rather than simply sensible."}, {"id": "sde84021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "What is a 'motif' in literature?", "options": ["the main character of a story", "a recurring image, symbol, or idea that appears throughout a text", "the setting of a story", "the final twist in a plot"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A motif is a recurring image, symbol, or idea that appears repeatedly throughout a text, often reinforcing a theme.", "hint": "Think about an image or idea that keeps reappearing throughout a story or poem."}, {"id": "sde84022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Poetry Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "In poetry, what is 'enjambment'?", "options": ["a rhyme at the end of every line", "when a sentence or phrase continues onto the next line without a pause or punctuation mark", "a poem with no title", "a type of metaphor only"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Enjambment occurs when a sentence or phrase runs on from one line of poetry to the next without a pause, rather than ending neatly at the line break.", "hint": "Think about when an idea continues onto the next line, rather than stopping cleanly with the line break."}, {"id": "sde84023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "What is the effect of using short, fragmented sentences in a tense scene of a story?", "options": ["it usually slows the pace and creates a relaxed mood", "it can create urgency, tension, or a feeling of breathlessness", "it always indicates a happy ending", "it has no real effect on the reader"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Short, fragmented sentences often speed up the pace of reading, which can create a sense of urgency, tension, or breathlessness in a scene.", "hint": "Think about how reading short, quick sentences might affect your sense of pacing and tension."}, {"id": "sde84024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "What is a 'symbol' in literature?", "options": ["a word that rhymes with another", "an object, person, or image that represents a deeper meaning beyond its literal self", "the title of a poem", "a type of punctuation mark"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A symbol is an object, person, or image that represents a deeper meaning or idea beyond its literal, surface-level self.", "hint": "Think about an object in a story that represents something bigger than just itself, like a dove representing peace."}, {"id": "sde84025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "8", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G8-E4", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates juxtaposition (placing two contrasting ideas close together for effect)?", "options": ["The cat sat quietly on the warm windowsill.", "The bustling, chaotic market square sat beside the silent, empty cathedral.", "She walked slowly down the street.", "The sky was a clear, pale blue."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Placing the 'bustling, chaotic market square' directly beside the 'silent, empty cathedral' creates juxtaposition, highlighting the contrast between the two scenes.", "hint": "Look for the option that places two strongly contrasting images or ideas right next to each other."}, {"id": "sde91001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read: 'The Substitute\n\nEli had covered for absent colleagues a hundred times before, but never for a subject he'd actively avoided since his own school years. \"It's just supervision,\" the principal had said, not quite meeting his eyes. \"The students are working through a unit independently. You won't need to teach anything.\" This had turned out to be only partially true.\n\nWithin ten minutes, a girl in the back row raised her hand with a question about quadratic functions that Eli understood, in the abstract, was something he should know. He didn't. He said as much, which surprised her more than his answer would have. \"Most subs just make something up,\" she said, not unkindly. \"Or they pretend they're 'letting us figure it out ourselves.'\"\n\nWhat followed was not, by any reasonable measure, a successful lesson. Eli admitted his own confusion, then suggested they work through the problem together, using nothing but the textbook and a willingness to be visibly, uncomfortably wrong in front of fifteen sceptical fourteen-year-olds. Several students seemed to find this more interesting than any actual lesson on the topic. One pointed out, with the particular cruelty of teenagers, that he was \"worse at this than literally anyone in this room.\" She wasn't wrong.\n\nBy the end of the period, they had not fully solved the original problem, but had made what Eli considered genuine progress, partly through the textbook and partly through a particularly patient student named Marcus, who seemed to enjoy the novel experience of explaining something to an adult who was paying real attention. Eli left the classroom with no illusions about having taught mathematics that day. He had, perhaps, taught something else — though he couldn't have said exactly what, and suspected it wouldn't show up on any test.'\n\nWhy did Eli initially expect the substitute role to be straightforward?", "options": ["he had taught this exact subject many times before", "the principal told him it was 'just supervision' and that he wouldn't need to teach anything", "he had specifically requested this assignment", "the students had warned him it would be easy"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states the principal told him 'it's just supervision' and that 'you won't need to teach anything'.", "hint": "Look at the first paragraph for what the principal told Eli before the class began."}, {"id": "sde91002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the student's comment about subs 'pretending they're letting us figure it out ourselves' suggest about her past experiences?", "options": ["she has never had a substitute teacher before", "she has previously encountered substitutes who disguised their own lack of knowledge", "she believes all substitute teachers are highly skilled", "she has no opinion about substitute teachers"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This comment suggests she has seen this evasive pattern before, recognising it as a common cover for a substitute's own uncertainty.", "hint": "Think about what kind of past experience would lead a student to recognise and call out this specific pattern."}, {"id": "sde91003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nHow did Eli respond when he didn't know the answer to the student's question?", "options": ["he made up an answer to avoid embarrassment", "he admitted his confusion honestly and suggested working through it together", "he refused to engage with the question at all", "he sent the student to another teacher"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states Eli 'admitted his own confusion, then suggested they work through the problem together'.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for Eli's specific response to not knowing the answer."}, {"id": "sde91004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat role did Marcus play in the events of the passage?", "options": ["he caused the disruption in class", "he patiently helped explain the problem to Eli", "he was the principal's assistant", "he refused to participate in the lesson"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage describes Marcus as 'a particularly patient student... who seemed to enjoy the novel experience of explaining something to an adult who was paying real attention'.", "hint": "Look at the fourth paragraph for Marcus's specific contribution to the lesson."}, {"id": "sde91005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the final paragraph suggest Eli actually accomplished that day, despite not teaching mathematics successfully?", "options": ["nothing at all of value", "something harder to define, possibly related to honesty or genuine engagement, though the passage doesn't specify exactly what", "he successfully taught the entire unit on quadratic functions", "he convinced the students to dislike mathematics even more"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states he 'had, perhaps, taught something else — though he couldn't have said exactly what', suggesting an intangible but real outcome distinct from the maths content itself.", "hint": "Look at the very end of the passage for the deliberately vague but meaningful claim made about what Eli accomplished."}, {"id": "sde91006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the effect of the phrase 'with the particular cruelty of teenagers' in the third paragraph?", "options": ["it suggests genuine, serious cruelty intended to harm Eli", "it uses a knowing, slightly humorous tone to describe a typically blunt teenage comment, without implying real malice", "it proves the student hated Eli personally", "it has no real effect on the reader"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This phrase uses a knowing, wry tone to describe the bluntness typical of teenage honesty, without suggesting the comment was meant with genuine malice.", "hint": "Think about whether this phrase is meant entirely seriously, or with a touch of wry humour."}, {"id": "sde91007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Text Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of this passage?", "options": ["a character fails completely with no redeeming outcome", "a character experiences an unexpected, humbling situation that leads to an ambiguous but meaningful outcome", "a straightforward, successful lesson with no complications", "an argument for why substitute teachers should always know every subject"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage follows Eli through an unexpected, humbling classroom experience that, despite not achieving its original academic goal, leads to a genuine if hard-to-define positive outcome.", "hint": "Think about how the passage moves from an expected simple task to something more complicated and ultimately meaningful."}, {"id": "sde91008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'sceptical' mean in the third paragraph?", "options": ["fully trusting and convinced", "doubtful or unconvinced", "extremely excited", "completely indifferent"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Sceptical\" means doubtful or unconvinced, describing the students' likely attitude toward Eli's ability to help them.", "hint": "Think about a word describing an attitude of doubt rather than trust."}, {"id": "sde91009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read: 'Should Voting Be Compulsory for Young People?\n\nAustralia is one of a relatively small number of countries with compulsory voting, a system that has shaped its political culture in ways often invisible to those who have never experienced the alternative. As debates continue in various countries about lowering the voting age to sixteen, a related question deserves equal attention: should voting itself be made compulsory for younger citizens once they become eligible?\n\nProponents of compulsory voting for young people argue it would address one of the most persistent patterns in electoral politics worldwide: chronically low youth turnout in voluntary voting systems. When voting is optional, younger citizens — busy, often transient, frequently less attached to a fixed electorate — vote at consistently lower rates than older generations. This creates a feedback loop, proponents argue: politicians, rationally responding to who actually votes, tend to prioritise the concerns of older, more reliable voting blocs, further alienating younger citizens who see their interests consistently deprioritised.\n\nCritics raise a more fundamental objection: that voting is properly understood as a right, and rights, almost by definition, include the right not to exercise them. Forcing political participation, they argue, sits uneasily with the broader principle of individual liberty in a democracy, regardless of whether the policy goal (higher youth engagement) is laudable. Some critics also question whether compulsion produces genuine engagement at all, or merely produces uninformed, resentful votes cast purely to avoid a fine — arguably worse for democratic health than honest abstention.\n\nDefenders of compulsory voting counter that this critique, while philosophically coherent, may overstate the practical distinction between a 'right' and a 'civic duty'. Jury duty, they note, is compulsory in many democracies despite also being framed as participation in a fundamental civic institution; few object to this on the same philosophical grounds. Whether voting is meaningfully different from jury duty in this respect remains genuinely contested, rather than self-evident.\n\nWhat seems clearest, amid this disagreement, is that the debate over compulsory voting for young people sits at the intersection of two legitimate democratic values — broad political participation, and individual liberty — that do not always point in the same direction. Resolving this tension may say as much about a society's underlying political philosophy as it does about voter turnout statistics.'\n\nWhat pattern do proponents of compulsory voting for young people identify in voluntary voting systems?", "options": ["young people vote at higher rates than older generations", "youth turnout is chronically low compared to older generations", "voting rates are identical across all age groups", "compulsory voting has never been tried anywhere"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states proponents point to 'chronically low youth turnout in voluntary voting systems' as a persistent pattern.", "hint": "Look at the second paragraph for the specific pattern identified."}, {"id": "sde91010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat 'feedback loop' do proponents describe regarding politicians' behaviour?", "options": ["politicians ignore all voters equally", "politicians prioritise the concerns of older, more reliable voting blocs, further alienating younger citizens", "politicians always favour younger voters", "there is no connection between voter turnout and political priorities"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage describes politicians 'rationally responding to who actually votes', tending 'to prioritise the concerns of older, more reliable voting blocs, further alienating younger citizens'.", "hint": "Look at the end of the second paragraph for the specific cycle described."}, {"id": "sde91011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the critics' more 'fundamental objection' to compulsory voting, beyond practical concerns?", "options": ["that voting takes too much time", "that voting is properly understood as a right, which inherently includes the right not to exercise it", "that young people are incapable of voting responsibly", "that compulsory voting is too expensive to administer"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states critics argue 'voting is properly understood as a right, and rights, almost by definition, include the right not to exercise them'.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for this specific philosophical objection."}, {"id": "sde91012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy do defenders of compulsory voting bring up jury duty in the fourth paragraph?", "options": ["to argue that jury duty should also be abolished", "to suggest that compulsory civic duties (like jury duty) are widely accepted elsewhere, challenging the idea that voting must be entirely voluntary as a 'right'", "to prove that voting and jury duty are completely unrelated", "to argue that young people should be exempt from jury duty"], "answer": 1, "exp": "By comparing voting to jury duty (another compulsory civic institution that's widely accepted), defenders challenge the idea that compulsion is automatically incompatible with something being a 'right'.", "hint": "Think about why comparing voting to another already-accepted compulsory duty might support the defenders' argument."}, {"id": "sde91013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's own conclusion in the final paragraph?", "options": ["compulsory voting for young people is clearly correct and should be implemented immediately", "the debate involves a genuine tension between two legitimate democratic values, without an obviously correct resolution", "critics of compulsory voting are entirely wrong", "the issue has nothing to do with political philosophy"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer concludes that the debate 'sits at the intersection of two legitimate democratic values... that do not always point in the same direction', without declaring one side simply correct.", "hint": "Look at the final paragraph for the writer's own balanced assessment of the debate."}, {"id": "sde91014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'laudable' mean in the third paragraph?", "options": ["worthy of praise", "completely false", "extremely loud", "controversial and divisive"], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Laudable\" means worthy of praise, describing how critics acknowledge the GOAL of higher youth engagement, even while objecting to the method of compulsion.", "hint": "Think about a word describing something admirable or praiseworthy, even if you disagree with how it's achieved."}, {"id": "sde91015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Text Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of this passage?", "options": ["a one-sided persuasive essay arguing strongly for one position", "a balanced exploration of multiple perspectives on a genuinely contested issue, without declaring a single 'winner'", "a simple factual report with no differing viewpoints", "a personal narrative about the writer's own voting experience"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage presents both proponents' and critics' arguments, along with a response and counter-response, concluding that the tension reflects genuinely competing values rather than declaring one side simply correct.", "hint": "Think about whether the passage argues strongly for one side, or explores multiple perspectives fairly."}, {"id": "sde91016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'transient' (as in 'transient lifestyle')?", "options": ["permanent", "temporary or short-lived", "extremely wealthy", "completely settled"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Temporary or short-lived\" matches the meaning of 'transient', describing something that doesn't last or stay in one place long.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that doesn't stay in one place for very long."}, {"id": "sde91017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'coherent'?", "options": ["logical", "clear", "confusing or disjointed", "organised"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Confusing or disjointed\" is the opposite of 'coherent', which describes something logical and clearly connected.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that doesn't make logical sense or hold together well."}, {"id": "sde91018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'contested' (as in a 'contested issue')?", "options": ["universally agreed upon", "disputed or argued over", "completely irrelevant", "clearly resolved"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Disputed or argued over\" matches the meaning of 'contested', describing something still actively debated.", "hint": "Think of a word describing an issue that people still disagree strongly about."}, {"id": "sde91019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'self-evident'?", "options": ["obvious", "clear", "requiring proof or argument to establish", "instantly recognisable"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Requiring proof or argument to establish\" is the opposite of 'self-evident', which describes something obviously true without needing explanation.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that needs to be argued for, rather than being immediately obvious."}, {"id": "sde91020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'deprioritised'?", "options": ["given top priority", "given lower priority or importance", "completely ignored forever", "celebrated"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Given lower priority or importance\" matches the meaning of 'deprioritised', describing something pushed down the list of importance.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something moved further down a list of priorities."}, {"id": "sde91021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'alienating'?", "options": ["welcoming or including", "excluding", "confusing", "distancing"], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Welcoming or including\" is the opposite of 'alienating', which describes making someone feel excluded or distant.", "hint": "Think of a word describing the opposite of pushing someone away or excluding them."}, {"id": "sde91022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'philosophically coherent'?", "options": ["logically consistent within a system of ideas", "completely random", "emotionally driven only", "scientifically proven"], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Logically consistent within a system of ideas\" matches the meaning here, describing an argument that holds together logically within its own framework.", "hint": "Think about an argument that makes sense within its own logical framework, even if you disagree with its conclusion."}, {"id": "sde91023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'compulsory'?", "options": ["mandatory", "required", "optional", "essential"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Optional\" is the opposite of 'compulsory', which describes something required rather than a free choice.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something you can choose to do or not do, rather than being forced."}, {"id": "sde91024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'persistent' (as in a 'persistent pattern')?", "options": ["temporary", "continuing over a long time, without stopping", "completely random", "rare"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Continuing over a long time, without stopping\" matches the meaning of 'persistent', describing something that keeps occurring repeatedly.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that keeps happening again and again, refusing to go away."}, {"id": "sde91025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'genuine' (as in 'genuine engagement')?", "options": ["authentic", "sincere", "fake or insincere", "honest"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Fake or insincere\" is the opposite of 'genuine', which describes something authentic and real.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that only appears real, but isn't actually sincere."}, {"id": "sde92001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Subjunctive Mood", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of the subjunctive mood in a formal recommendation?", "options": ["I recommend that he attends the meeting.", "I recommend that he attend the meeting.", "I recommend that he will attend the meeting.", "I recommend that he attended the meeting."], "answer": 1, "exp": "After verbs like 'recommend' expressing a wish or suggestion, the subjunctive uses the base form of the verb regardless of subject: \"I recommend that he attend the meeting.\"", "hint": "After verbs like 'recommend', 'suggest', or 'insist', the subjunctive uses the base verb form, not the usual third-person -s ending."}, {"id": "sde92002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Clauses", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Identify the type of clause in this sentence: 'What she said surprised everyone in the room.'", "options": ["adjective clause", "adverbial clause", "noun clause functioning as the subject", "independent clause only"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"What she said\" functions as the subject of the sentence, acting as a noun clause.", "hint": "Think about what role this clause plays — is it acting as the subject, describing something, or modifying a verb?"}, {"id": "sde92003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Active and Passive Voice", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates correct use of the passive voice to emphasise the action over the actor?", "options": ["The committee rejected the proposal.", "The proposal was rejected.", "The committee is rejecting the proposal.", "The committee will reject the proposal."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"The proposal was rejected\" uses the passive voice and omits the actor entirely, placing full emphasis on the action and its result rather than who performed it.", "hint": "Look for the option that removes the actor entirely, focusing only on the action."}, {"id": "sde92004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Clauses", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence contains a non-finite clause?", "options": ["She finished her homework before dinner.", "To succeed in this field requires patience and persistence.", "She is finishing her homework now.", "She finished her homework, and then she relaxed."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"To succeed in this field\" is a non-finite clause (using an infinitive verb form), functioning as the subject of the sentence.", "hint": "Look for a clause using an infinitive ('to' + verb) rather than a fully conjugated verb."}, {"id": "sde92005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Punctuation — Dashes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of an em dash to indicate an abrupt change in thought?", "options": ["She was about to leave — then the phone rang.", "She was, about to leave then, the phone — rang.", "She was about — to leave then the phone rang.", "She was about to leave then — the — phone rang."], "answer": 0, "exp": "An em dash can indicate an abrupt break or change in thought, placed naturally where the interruption occurs: \"She was about to leave — then the phone rang.\"", "hint": "The dash should be placed exactly where the interruption or sudden shift occurs."}, {"id": "sde92006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Infinitives", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which word in this sentence is functioning as an infinitive? 'She wants to travel next year.'", "options": ["wants", "to travel", "next", "year"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"To travel\" is an infinitive — the base form of a verb preceded by 'to', functioning here as the object of 'wants'.", "hint": "An infinitive is the word 'to' followed by the base form of a verb."}, {"id": "sde92007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Punctuation — Semicolons", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses a semicolon to join two closely related independent clauses?", "options": ["The weather improved; we decided to go for a hike.", "The weather improved, we decided to go for a hike.", "The weather improved; and we decided to go for a hike.", "The weather; improved we decided to go for a hike."], "answer": 0, "exp": "A semicolon correctly joins two closely related independent clauses without needing a conjunction: \"The weather improved; we decided to go for a hike.\"", "hint": "A semicolon alone (without 'and') can join two complete, related sentences."}, {"id": "sde92008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Gerunds", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates correct use of a gerund phrase as the subject?", "options": ["Swimming every morning improved her fitness significantly.", "She improved her fitness by swimming every morning.", "Improved fitness, swimming every morning, was her goal.", "Her fitness improved, swimming every morning was the cause."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Swimming every morning\" functions as a gerund phrase acting as the subject of the sentence.", "hint": "Look for a phrase beginning with an '-ing' verb form, acting as the subject of the sentence."}, {"id": "sde92009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Parallel Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly demonstrates parallel structure in a complex list?", "options": ["The plan requires careful budgeting, clear communication, and to monitor progress regularly.", "The plan requires careful budgeting, clear communication, and regular progress monitoring.", "The plan requires to budget carefully, clear communication, and regular monitoring.", "The plan requires careful budgeting, communicating clearly, and to monitor regularly."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Parallel structure requires consistent grammatical form throughout the list: \"careful budgeting, clear communication, and regular progress monitoring\" all use a noun-phrase structure consistently.", "hint": "Check that every item in the list uses the same grammatical form throughout."}, {"id": "sde92010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Subjunctive Mood", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of the past subjunctive in a hypothetical statement?", "options": ["If she was taller, she would have made the team.", "If she were taller, she would have made the team.", "If she is taller, she would have made the team.", "If she will be taller, she would have made the team."], "answer": 1, "exp": "For hypothetical or contrary-to-fact statements introduced by 'if', the subjunctive uses 'were' rather than 'was': \"If she were taller...\"", "hint": "For hypothetical 'if' statements, the correct form is 'were', regardless of the subject."}, {"id": "sde92011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Appositives", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of an appositive phrase to add information concisely?", "options": ["My colleague Sarah, an experienced surgeon, led the operation.", "My colleague, Sarah an experienced, surgeon led the operation.", "My colleague Sarah an experienced surgeon, led, the operation.", "My colleague, Sarah, an experienced, surgeon led the operation."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"An experienced surgeon\" is an appositive phrase, correctly set off with a comma, renaming and adding information about 'Sarah'.", "hint": "The appositive phrase should be set off clearly with commas, without unnecessary commas elsewhere."}, {"id": "sde92012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Sentence Fragments", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates a sentence fragment (an error)?", "options": ["Because the storm hit suddenly.", "The storm hit suddenly.", "Because the storm hit suddenly, we evacuated immediately.", "The storm, which hit suddenly, caused significant damage."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Because the storm hit suddenly\" is a sentence fragment — a dependent clause presented alone, without a main clause to complete the thought.", "hint": "Look for a clause that depends on something else to complete its meaning, but is left standing alone."}, {"id": "sde92013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Who vs Whom", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses the word 'whom' as the object of a preposition?", "options": ["To whom should I address this letter?", "To who should I address this letter?", "Whom should address this letter?", "To whom did address this letter?"], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Whom\" is correct as the object of the preposition 'to': \"To whom should I address this letter?\"", "hint": "Use 'whom' when the word follows a preposition like 'to', 'for', or 'with'."}, {"id": "sde92014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Punctuation — Colons", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of a colon to introduce a formal list?", "options": ["The committee approved three measures: funding, staffing, and oversight.", "The committee approved three measures, funding: staffing, and oversight.", "The committee approved: three measures funding, staffing, and oversight.", "The committee approved three: measures funding, staffing, and oversight."], "answer": 0, "exp": "A colon correctly introduces a formal list after a complete independent clause: \"The committee approved three measures: funding, staffing, and oversight.\"", "hint": "The colon should follow a complete sentence, introducing the list that follows."}, {"id": "sde92015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Verb Tense", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates correct use of the present perfect continuous tense?", "options": ["She has been working on this project for three months.", "She works on this project for three months.", "She worked on this project for three months.", "She will work on this project for three months."], "answer": 0, "exp": "Present perfect continuous tense uses 'has/have been' plus an '-ing' verb form to describe an ongoing action that started in the past and continues: \"She has been working...\"", "hint": "This tense uses 'has been' or 'have been' combined with an '-ing' verb form."}, {"id": "sde92016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Modifiers", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence avoids a dangling modifier?", "options": ["Having finished the report, the manager submitted it for approval.", "Having finished the report, it was submitted for approval by the manager.", "The report was submitted by the manager, having finished it.", "Having finished, the report was submitted for approval."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Having finished the report, the manager submitted it\" correctly places the modifying phrase next to 'the manager', who actually performed the finishing.", "hint": "The opening modifying phrase should clearly and logically describe the subject that immediately follows it."}, {"id": "sde92017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Clauses", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of an adverbial clause of concession?", "options": ["Although the evidence was weak, the jury reached a verdict.", "Because the evidence was weak, the jury reached a verdict.", "When the evidence was weak, the jury reached a verdict.", "Where the evidence was weak, the jury reached a verdict."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Although the evidence was weak\" is an adverbial clause of concession, acknowledging a contrasting point before the main clause.", "hint": "Look for a clause that acknowledges something contrary or surprising in relation to the main clause, often starting with 'although' or 'even though'."}, {"id": "sde92018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Subject-Verb Agreement", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates correct subject-verb agreement with an indefinite pronoun?", "options": ["Everyone in the class has submitted their assignment.", "Everyone in the class have submitted their assignment.", "Everyone in the class are submitting their assignment.", "Everyone in the class were submitting their assignment."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Everyone\" is treated as singular, requiring a singular verb form: \"Everyone... has submitted...\"", "hint": "Indefinite pronouns like 'everyone', 'someone', and 'nobody' are usually treated as singular."}, {"id": "sde92019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Sentence Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of a cleft sentence for emphasis?", "options": ["It was Sarah who solved the problem.", "Sarah solved the problem, it was her.", "It Sarah was who solved the problem.", "Sarah was it who solved the problem."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"It was Sarah who solved the problem\" is a cleft sentence, restructuring the standard sentence to place emphasis specifically on 'Sarah'.", "hint": "A cleft sentence often begins with 'It was...' or 'It is...' to emphasise a specific element."}, {"id": "sde92020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Pronoun Reference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly avoids ambiguous pronoun reference?", "options": ["When Sarah met Lucy, she gave her a book.", "When Sarah met Lucy, Sarah gave Lucy a book.", "She met her, and she gave her a book.", "When Sarah met her, she gave her a book."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Using the actual names \"Sarah gave Lucy a book\" avoids the ambiguity created by multiple unclear pronouns referring to two different female subjects.", "hint": "Look for the sentence that clearly identifies who is doing what, rather than relying on ambiguous pronouns."}, {"id": "sde92021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Absolute Phrases", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates the correct use of an absolute phrase?", "options": ["Her hands trembling, she opened the envelope.", "Her hands, trembling she opened, the envelope.", "Trembling her hands, she opened the envelope.", "She opened the envelope, her hands trembling, was nervous."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Her hands trembling\" is an absolute phrase, modifying the entire main clause rather than a single word, correctly placed at the start of the sentence.", "hint": "An absolute phrase typically contains a noun followed by a participle, modifying the whole sentence rather than one specific word."}, {"id": "sde92022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Commonly Confused Words", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly demonstrates the distinction between 'affect' and 'effect'?", "options": ["The new policy will affect many employees, with significant effects on morale.", "The new policy will effect many employees, with significant affects on morale.", "The new policy will affect many employees, with significant affects on morale.", "The new policy will effect many employees, with significant effects on morale, incorrectly."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Affect\" is typically used as a verb (to influence), and \"effect\" is typically used as a noun (a result): \"will affect... with significant effects...\"", "hint": "Remember: 'affect' is usually the verb (an action), 'effect' is usually the noun (a result)."}, {"id": "sde92023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Grammar — Absolute Phrases", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates a correctly punctuated nominative absolute construction with no errors?", "options": ["The meeting concluded, everyone satisfied with the outcome.", "The meeting, concluded everyone satisfied, with the outcome.", "The meeting concluded everyone, satisfied with the outcome.", "The meeting concluded everyone satisfied with the outcome no comma."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"The meeting concluded, everyone satisfied with the outcome\" correctly uses a comma to separate the main clause from the absolute phrase describing the resulting state.", "hint": "Look for correct comma placement separating the main action from the descriptive phrase that follows."}, {"id": "sde92024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Commonly Confused Words", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses 'lay' versus 'lie'?", "options": ["She decided to lay down for a nap.", "She decided to lie down for a nap.", "She decided to lied down for a nap.", "She decided to laid down for a nap."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Lie\" (meaning to recline) is correct here, since 'lay' requires a direct object (as in 'lay the book down'), which is missing in this sentence.", "hint": "\"Lie\" means to recline yourself; \"lay\" means to place something else down, and needs an object."}, {"id": "sde92025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Writer's Craft — Sentence Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly demonstrates the use of a rhetorical fragment for deliberate stylistic effect?", "options": ["She had one thought as the door closed. Silence.", "She had one thought, as the door closed silence.", "She had one, thought as the door closed silence.", "She had one thought as, the door closed. Silence."], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"Silence.\" used deliberately as a one-word sentence fragment can create dramatic emphasis, a stylistic technique distinct from an accidental grammatical error.", "hint": "Look for the option that uses a short, deliberate fragment for stylistic emphasis, with correct punctuation elsewhere."}, {"id": "sde93001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'circumspect'?", "options": ["reckless", "cautious and careful about consequences", "loud", "generous"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Cautious and careful about consequences\" matches the meaning of 'circumspect', describing careful, wary behaviour.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who carefully considers consequences before acting."}, {"id": "sde93002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'unequivocal'?", "options": ["clear", "certain", "ambiguous or unclear", "definite"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Ambiguous or unclear\" is the opposite of 'unequivocal', which describes something stated with complete clarity, leaving no room for doubt.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something open to more than one interpretation."}, {"id": "sde93003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Word Origins — Roots", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "The root word 'morph' relates to which concept?", "options": ["shape or form", "colour", "sound", "time"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The root 'morph' relates to shape or form, as in 'metamorphosis' (a change in form) or 'amorphous' (without a defined shape).", "hint": "Think of words like 'metamorphosis' or 'amorphous'."}, {"id": "sde93004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Word Origins — Suffixes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "The suffix '-itis' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["inflammation or disease, especially in medical terms", "speed", "a type of government", "colour"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The suffix '-itis' relates to inflammation or disease, as in 'arthritis' (inflammation of the joints) or 'tonsillitis'.", "hint": "Think of medical terms like 'arthritis' or 'bronchitis'."}, {"id": "sde93005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "A politician says, 'Either we pass this law immediately, or our economy collapses entirely.' What persuasive fallacy is this an example of?", "options": ["a false dilemma, presenting only two extreme options when other possibilities exist", "a valid statistic", "an appeal to authority", "onomatopoeia"], "answer": 0, "exp": "This is a false dilemma, presenting only two extreme outcomes as if no other possibilities exist, which oversimplifies a likely more complex situation.", "hint": "Think about whether there might realistically be other outcomes besides these two extremes."}, {"id": "sde93006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'capricious'?", "options": ["predictable", "unpredictable and impulsive", "extremely calm", "carefully planned"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Unpredictable and impulsive\" matches the meaning of 'capricious', describing sudden, unpredictable changes in mood or behaviour.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone whose mood or decisions change suddenly and unpredictably."}, {"id": "sde93007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "A writer argues against a policy by attacking the personal character of its supporter, rather than the policy's actual merits. What is this technique called?", "options": ["ad hominem (attacking the person rather than the argument)", "a statistic", "a rhetorical question", "an analogy"], "answer": 0, "exp": "An ad hominem attack targets the person making an argument, rather than addressing the substance of the argument itself.", "hint": "Think about whether this technique addresses the actual policy, or instead attacks the person supporting it."}, {"id": "sde93008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'disparage'?", "options": ["to praise highly", "to criticise or belittle", "to ignore completely", "to celebrate"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"To criticise or belittle\" matches the meaning of 'disparage', describing speaking negatively about someone or something.", "hint": "Think of a word describing speaking dismissively or critically about someone."}, {"id": "sde93009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Word Origins — Prefixes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "The prefix 'post-' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["before", "after", "during", "never"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The prefix 'post-' relates to 'after', as in 'postpone' (to put after) or 'post-war' (after a war).", "hint": "Think of words like 'postpone' or 'postscript'."}, {"id": "sde93010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'magnanimous'?", "options": ["generous", "forgiving", "petty or mean-spirited", "noble"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Petty or mean-spirited\" is the opposite of 'magnanimous', which describes generous, noble behaviour, especially toward a rival or someone less powerful.", "hint": "Think of a word describing the opposite of generous, noble behaviour toward others."}, {"id": "sde93011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "A speaker claims, 'This policy has worked in every country that's tried it' without citing any actual examples or evidence. What is this an example of?", "options": ["an unsupported generalisation, presented as though it were established fact", "a verified statistic", "a logical syllogism", "an analogy"], "answer": 0, "exp": "This is an unsupported generalisation — a sweeping claim presented confidently, but without any specific, checkable evidence to support it.", "hint": "Think about whether this claim provides any specific, checkable evidence, or just a vague, sweeping assertion."}, {"id": "sde93012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'vindictive'?", "options": ["forgiving", "seeking revenge", "generous", "calm"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Seeking revenge\" matches the meaning of 'vindictive', describing a desire to harm someone in return for a perceived wrong.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone determined to get revenge on someone who wronged them."}, {"id": "sde93013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "A writer uses a deliberately understated tone to describe a catastrophic event, saying only 'it was a bit of a setback'. What technique is this?", "options": ["hyperbole", "litotes/understatement, for ironic or dramatic effect", "alliteration", "onomatopoeia"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This is understatement (litotes), deliberately downplaying something serious for ironic or dramatic effect, the opposite of hyperbole.", "hint": "Think about the opposite of exaggeration — deliberately making something sound smaller or less significant than it is."}, {"id": "sde93014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'equanimity'?", "options": ["panic", "calmness, especially under pressure", "excitement", "confusion"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Calmness, especially under pressure\" matches the meaning of 'equanimity', describing a composed, even temperament in difficult situations.", "hint": "Think of a word describing staying calm and composed, even when things get difficult."}, {"id": "sde93015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Word Origins — Roots", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "The root word 'gen' relates to which concept?", "options": ["birth, origin, or production", "light", "sound", "movement"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The root 'gen' relates to birth, origin, or production, as in 'generate' (to produce) or 'genesis' (the origin of something).", "hint": "Think of words like 'generate' or 'genetics'."}, {"id": "sde93016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'austere'?", "options": ["plain", "strict", "luxurious or indulgent", "simple"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Luxurious or indulgent\" is the opposite of 'austere', which describes a plain, strict, or self-disciplined style or lifestyle.", "hint": "Think of a word describing the opposite of a plain, strict, simple lifestyle."}, {"id": "sde93017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "A persuasive essay opens with a vivid personal anecdote before transitioning to statistical evidence. What is the likely purpose of starting with the anecdote?", "options": ["to confuse the reader before the real argument begins", "to create an emotional connection with the reader before presenting more objective evidence", "anecdotes have no persuasive function at all", "to fill space without adding any value"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Opening with a personal anecdote often creates an emotional connection with the reader, making the subsequent, more objective evidence feel more personally relevant.", "hint": "Think about why a writer might want readers to feel something before presenting more abstract facts and figures."}, {"id": "sde93018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'obfuscate'?", "options": ["to clarify completely", "to deliberately make something unclear or confusing", "to celebrate openly", "to simplify helpfully"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"To deliberately make something unclear or confusing\" matches the meaning of 'obfuscate', often used to describe deliberately vague or confusing language.", "hint": "Think of a word describing deliberately confusing or unclear language, often used to hide something."}, {"id": "sde93019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "A writer states, 'Critics of this plan have never actually read it in full' as a way to dismiss their objections, without addressing the objections themselves. What technique is this closest to?", "options": ["a straw man / ad hominem-style dismissal, deflecting from the substance of the actual criticism", "a valid statistical rebuttal", "a logical syllogism", "an extended metaphor"], "answer": 0, "exp": "This dismissal deflects from addressing the actual substance of the criticism, instead attacking the critics' credibility or knowledge — a tactic similar to both straw man and ad hominem techniques.", "hint": "Think about whether this response actually engages with the critics' specific objections, or simply dismisses them."}, {"id": "sde93020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'tenable' (as in a 'tenable argument')?", "options": ["impossible to defend", "reasonably defensible or justifiable", "completely proven beyond doubt", "emotionally persuasive only"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Reasonably defensible or justifiable\" matches the meaning of 'tenable', describing a position that can be reasonably maintained or defended.", "hint": "Think of a word describing an argument that can reasonably be defended, even if not absolutely proven."}, {"id": "sde93021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Word Origins — Suffixes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "The suffix '-phile' usually relates to which concept?", "options": ["a love or strong liking for something", "a fear of something", "a study of something", "a measurement of size"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The suffix '-phile' relates to a love or strong liking for something, as in 'bibliophile' (a lover of books) or 'audiophile' (a lover of high-quality sound).", "hint": "Think of words like 'bibliophile' or 'audiophile'."}, {"id": "sde93022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'pragmatic'?", "options": ["practical", "realistic", "idealistic, prioritising principle over practicality", "sensible"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Idealistic, prioritising principle over practicality\" is the opposite of 'pragmatic', which describes a realistic, results-focused approach.", "hint": "Think of a word describing someone who prioritises principles or ideals over practical considerations."}, {"id": "sde93023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Persuasive and Rhetorical Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "A persuasive speech ends with the line: 'History will judge us by what we do next.' What rhetorical effect does this create?", "options": ["it trivialises the issue being discussed", "it elevates the stakes of the decision, framing it as historically significant", "it provides a specific statistic", "it directly insults the audience"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This line elevates the perceived importance of the decision by framing it within a larger historical context, increasing the sense of stakes and urgency for the audience.", "hint": "Think about how invoking 'history' might make a decision feel more significant than it might otherwise seem."}, {"id": "sde93024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'inexorable'?", "options": ["easily stopped", "impossible to stop or prevent", "extremely fast", "completely random"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Impossible to stop or prevent\" matches the meaning of 'inexorable', describing something relentless and unstoppable.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that simply cannot be stopped or persuaded to change course."}, {"id": "sde93025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E3", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'ephemeral'?", "options": ["fleeting", "temporary", "permanent or lasting", "brief"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Permanent or lasting\" is the opposite of 'ephemeral', which describes something that lasts only a very short time.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that lasts a very long time, the opposite of brief."}, {"id": "sde94001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read: 'The Quiet Cost of Constant Connectivity\n\nThere is a particular kind of exhaustion that has no obvious cause — not physical labour, not lack of sleep, but something closer to a low-grade, persistent depletion that many people struggle to name. Increasingly, researchers studying attention and digital habits suspect that constant connectivity itself may be a significant, underappreciated contributor.\n\nThe argument runs roughly as follows: human attention, unlike a renewable resource, behaves more like a finite reservoir that depletes throughout the day, particularly when subjected to frequent task-switching. Every notification checked, every brief scroll through a feed between tasks, requires a small but real cognitive cost — not just the seconds spent looking at the screen, but the additional, often unmeasured time required to re-establish focus on whatever was previously being done. Multiplied across dozens of these interruptions daily, the cumulative effect on sustained attention may be considerably larger than any individual interruption would suggest.\n\nThis is not, researchers are careful to note, an argument that technology itself is inherently harmful — a framing that risks oversimplifying a genuinely complex relationship between digital tools and wellbeing. Many of the same notifications and connectivity features that fragment attention also provide genuine value: coordination with colleagues, connection with distant family, access to information that would have been unreachable in any previous era. The relevant question is not whether to use these tools, but how their design and our habits around them might be adjusted to reduce unnecessary cognitive cost without sacrificing genuine benefit.\n\nSome proposed interventions are individual: scheduled 'focus blocks' with notifications disabled, or simply relocating a phone to another room during demanding work. Others are structural, aimed at the technology itself — design choices like reducing the urgency signalled by notification design, or building in natural points where checking a device feels less compulsive. Early evidence for both approaches is promising but limited, constrained by the practical difficulty of conducting rigorous, long-term studies on rapidly evolving technology and equally rapidly evolving habits.\n\nWhat seems least disputed, even among researchers who disagree on specific interventions, is the underlying premise: attention is a limited resource, constant interruption has a real and measurable cost, and the convenience of permanent connectivity is not, in fact, free.'\n\nWhat 'particular kind of exhaustion' does the passage describe in the opening paragraph?", "options": ["exhaustion clearly caused by physical labour", "a low-grade, persistent depletion with no obvious physical cause", "exhaustion that only affects elderly people", "exhaustion caused entirely by lack of sleep"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage describes 'a low-grade, persistent depletion' that is 'not physical labour, not lack of sleep', with researchers suspecting connectivity as a contributing cause.", "hint": "Look at the first paragraph for the specific description of this unusual kind of tiredness."}, {"id": "sde94002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nAccording to the second paragraph, what is the 'cumulative effect' of frequent task-switching on attention?", "options": ["it has no measurable effect at all", "it may be considerably larger than any single interruption would suggest, due to the additional time needed to refocus", "it only affects physical energy, not mental focus", "it improves attention over time through practice"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states the cumulative effect 'may be considerably larger than any individual interruption would suggest', due to the additional time needed to re-establish focus after each interruption.", "hint": "Look at the end of the second paragraph for the specific claim about cumulative effects."}, {"id": "sde94003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer explicitly state this is 'not an argument that technology itself is inherently harmful'?", "options": ["to avoid oversimplifying a genuinely complex relationship between digital tools and wellbeing, acknowledging real benefits alongside the costs", "because the writer secretly believes technology is completely harmless", "to contradict everything stated in the previous paragraph", "because this clarification is legally required"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The writer explicitly avoids this oversimplified framing 'that risks oversimplifying a genuinely complex relationship', going on to acknowledge genuine benefits of connectivity alongside its costs.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for the writer's stated reason for avoiding this simpler, more extreme framing."}, {"id": "sde94004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat distinction does the passage draw between 'individual' and 'structural' interventions?", "options": ["individual interventions involve personal habit changes, while structural interventions involve changes to technology design itself", "there is no real distinction between these two types of interventions", "structural interventions are always more effective than individual ones", "individual interventions only apply to teenagers"], "answer": 0, "exp": "The passage describes individual interventions as personal habit changes (like scheduled focus blocks), while structural interventions involve changes to 'the technology itself', such as notification design.", "hint": "Look at the fourth paragraph for the specific examples given of each type of intervention."}, {"id": "sde94005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat limitation does the passage acknowledge regarding evidence for these interventions?", "options": ["there is no evidence at all for any intervention", "evidence is promising but limited, constrained by the difficulty of studying rapidly evolving technology and habits", "all interventions have been proven completely ineffective", "researchers refuse to study this topic at all"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states 'early evidence for both approaches is promising but limited, constrained by the practical difficulty of conducting rigorous, long-term studies on rapidly evolving technology'.", "hint": "Look at the end of the fourth paragraph for the specific limitation acknowledged about the evidence."}, {"id": "sde94006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'depletion' mean in the first paragraph?", "options": ["sudden increase", "gradual reduction or exhaustion of a resource", "complete restoration", "an unrelated medical condition"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Depletion\" means a gradual reduction or exhaustion of a resource — in this context, the gradual reduction of mental attention or energy.", "hint": "Think about a resource being gradually used up over time."}, {"id": "sde94007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich claim does the writer describe as 'least disputed' even among researchers who disagree on specific interventions?", "options": ["that all technology should be banned immediately", "that attention is a limited resource and constant interruption has a real, measurable cost", "that notifications have no effect on focus whatsoever", "that only individual interventions are worth pursuing"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The final paragraph states the underlying premise that 'attention is a limited resource, constant interruption has a real and measurable cost' is least disputed, even amid disagreement on specific solutions.", "hint": "Look at the very last paragraph for the specific underlying claim described as least disputed."}, {"id": "sde94008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the overall purpose of this passage?", "options": ["to persuade readers to delete all social media immediately", "to inform readers about a nuanced, evidence-based perspective on attention and digital connectivity, without resorting to extreme claims", "to argue that connectivity has absolutely no downsides", "to provide a strict, mandatory daily schedule for phone use"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage presents a nuanced, evidence-based discussion of the costs and benefits of digital connectivity, explicitly avoiding extreme claims in either direction.", "hint": "Think about whether this passage argues for an extreme position, or presents a more balanced, careful perspective."}, {"id": "sde94009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read: 'What the Glacier Knows\n\nThey say it moves an inch a year, sometimes less,\na stillness so complete it reads as stone,\nuntil you press your palm against the white\nand feel, beneath your hand, the cold thing groan.\n\nMy grandfather walked this valley as a boy,\nwhen the ice reached further than the eye could hold.\nHe tells it now the way you'd tell a fable —\nhalf-memory, half-myth, slightly retold.\n\nI cannot prove which version is more true:\nthe boy who touched the ice where I stand now,\nor the old man's memory, worn smooth with telling,\nsoftened at the edges, somehow, somehow.\n\nWhat's certain is the line still carved in granite,\na high-water mark from a vanished century's reach —\nnot metaphor, not myth, not grandfather's fable,\njust rock, remembering what the ice used to teach.\n\nI photograph the gap between then and now,\nthe bare stone where blue ice used to gleam,\naware that what I'm framing in this picture\nis already, quietly, becoming someone's dream —\n\nthe version my own grandchild might later tell,\nhalf-myth themselves by then, slightly retold,\nof a grandparent who once stood where ice was vanishing,\nin a valley going quiet, and increasingly cold.'\n\nWhat does the speaker's grandfather describe in the second stanza?", "options": ["a fictional story with no basis in reality", "his own memory of the glacier reaching much further when he was young", "a scientific report on glacier movement", "a dream he once had"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem describes the grandfather recalling 'when the ice reached further than the eye could hold', a memory from his own youth.", "hint": "Look at the second stanza for what specifically the grandfather remembers and describes."}, {"id": "sde94010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the speaker mean by saying the grandfather's memory is told 'the way you'd tell a fable — half-memory, half-myth'?", "options": ["the grandfather is deliberately lying about his memory", "memories, especially retold many times, can blend factual recollection with embellishment over time", "fables and memories are scientifically identical", "the speaker doesn't trust the grandfather at all"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This phrase suggests that memories, especially when retold repeatedly over time, naturally blend genuine recollection with elements of embellishment or reshaping, similar to how a fable evolves.", "hint": "Think about how a memory might change subtly each time it's retold over many years."}, {"id": "sde94011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat physical evidence does the poem describe as 'certain', distinct from memory or storytelling?", "options": ["a photograph taken by the grandfather", "a line carved in granite marking the glacier's former height", "a written historical record", "nothing — the poem claims nothing is certain"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem describes 'the line still carved in granite, a high-water mark... not metaphor, not myth, not grandfather's fable, just rock' as the certain physical evidence.", "hint": "Look at the third stanza for the specific physical evidence described as certain, contrasted with memory and myth."}, {"id": "sde94012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the final stanza suggest about how the speaker's own experience will eventually be remembered?", "options": ["it will be perfectly preserved forever, unchanged", "it will likely become reshaped and partly mythologised over time, just as the grandfather's memory was, when retold by a future grandchild", "it will be completely forgotten immediately", "it has already been forgotten"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The final stanza suggests the speaker's own present experience will similarly become 'half-myth themselves by then, slightly retold' when eventually passed down to a future grandchild.", "hint": "Look at the final stanza for how the speaker imagines their own memory being passed on and changed over time."}, {"id": "sde94013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat is the overall theme of this poem?", "options": ["the precise scientific measurement of glacier movement", "the way memory, storytelling, and physical evidence each capture different, sometimes blurred versions of truth across generations, set against irreversible environmental change", "a simple description of a family hiking trip", "an argument that grandparents always exaggerate their stories"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem explores how memory, oral storytelling, and physical evidence (the carved line in granite) each capture different, sometimes blurred versions of truth across generations, set against the backdrop of the glacier's irreversible retreat.", "hint": "Think about how the poem weaves together personal memory, physical evidence, and environmental change across multiple generations."}, {"id": "sde94014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat literary device is used in the phrase 'feel, beneath your hand, the cold thing groan'?", "options": ["a literal, scientifically accurate description with no figurative meaning", "personification, giving the glacier a human-like sound and quality", "onomatopoeia only, with no other figurative meaning", "a simile comparing the glacier to a person"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This phrase personifies the glacier, giving it a human-like quality (groaning) to emphasise its massive, almost-alive presence despite its apparent stillness.", "hint": "Think about whether a glacier can literally 'groan', or whether this attributes a human-like quality to it."}, {"id": "sde94015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Evaluating Evidence", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhich phrase best captures the poem's central tension between permanence and change?", "options": ["\"They say it moves an inch a year, sometimes less\"", "\"the bare stone where blue ice used to gleam\"", "\"a high-water mark from a vanished century's reach\"", "all three phrases contribute to this tension, each highlighting a different aspect of change over time"], "answer": 3, "exp": "Each phrase highlights a different aspect of the tension between apparent permanence (slow movement, solid rock) and undeniable change (vanished ice, a bare landscape where ice once was).", "hint": "Consider whether more than one phrase meaningfully contributes to this central tension throughout the poem."}, {"id": "sde94016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhy might the poet have chosen to end the poem on the image of a future grandchild's retelling, rather than ending with the glacier itself?", "options": ["to suggest the cycle of memory and change will continue across future generations, extending the poem's themes beyond just the glacier's retreat", "to abruptly change the subject with no clear purpose", "because the poem ran out of things to say about the glacier", "to argue that grandchildren are unreliable narrators"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Ending on a future grandchild's eventual retelling extends the poem's themes of memory, change, and storytelling beyond the glacier itself, suggesting this cycle will continue indefinitely across generations.", "hint": "Think about how ending on this image connects back to the earlier themes about memory and retelling across generations."}, {"id": "sde94017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "What is 'dramatic irony'?", "options": ["when a character says something funny", "when the audience knows something a character does not, creating tension or insight", "a type of rhyme scheme", "a metaphor used in drama only"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Dramatic irony occurs when the audience or reader knows something important that a character within the story does not, often creating tension or deeper meaning.", "hint": "Think about the audience having information that a character on stage or in a story lacks."}, {"id": "sde94018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "What is a 'foil' in literature?", "options": ["a type of metal used in old books", "a character whose traits contrast with another character, highlighting particular qualities by contrast", "the main villain of a story", "a type of rhyming pattern"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A foil is a character whose contrasting traits highlight particular qualities in another character, often the protagonist, through comparison.", "hint": "Think about a character included specifically to highlight another character's traits by contrast."}, {"id": "sde94019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "What does 'pathos' refer to in rhetoric and literature?", "options": ["an appeal to logic and reason", "an appeal to the emotions of the audience", "an appeal to the credibility of the speaker", "a type of rhyme scheme"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Pathos refers to an appeal to the emotions of the audience, one of the three classical persuasive appeals alongside ethos (credibility) and logos (logic).", "hint": "This term, from the same root as 'sympathy' and 'empathy', relates to feelings."}, {"id": "sde94020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "What does 'ethos' refer to in rhetoric?", "options": ["an appeal to emotion", "an appeal based on the credibility or character of the speaker", "an appeal to statistics only", "a type of figurative language"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Ethos refers to an appeal based on the credibility, expertise, or character of the speaker, used to persuade an audience to trust their argument.", "hint": "This term relates to a speaker's perceived trustworthiness and credibility."}, {"id": "sde94021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "What does 'logos' refer to in rhetoric?", "options": ["an appeal to emotion", "an appeal to the speaker's character", "an appeal based on logic, reasoning, and evidence", "a poetic rhyme scheme"], "answer": 2, "exp": "Logos refers to an appeal based on logic, reasoning, and evidence, one of the three classical persuasive appeals.", "hint": "This term shares its root with words like 'logic' and 'logical'."}, {"id": "sde94022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "What is 'pathetic fallacy'?", "options": ["a logical error in an argument", "attributing human emotions to nature or inanimate objects, especially to reflect a character's mood", "a type of rhyme scheme", "an appeal to the audience's pity"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Pathetic fallacy is a specific type of personification where nature or the weather is given human emotions, often used to reflect or amplify a character's internal mood (such as a storm reflecting inner turmoil).", "hint": "Think about a stormy sky described as 'angry', reflecting a character's own anger."}, {"id": "sde94023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "What is an 'unreliable narrator'?", "options": ["a narrator who tells the story in the wrong order", "a narrator whose credibility or perception is compromised, leading readers to question their version of events", "a narrator who never speaks", "a narrator who exists only in poetry"], "answer": 1, "exp": "An unreliable narrator is one whose credibility, knowledge, or honesty is compromised in some way, leading readers to question the accuracy of their account of events.", "hint": "Think about a narrator whose account of events readers might have good reason to doubt."}, {"id": "sde94024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "What is 'in medias res'?", "options": ["starting a story in the middle of the action, rather than at the very beginning", "ending a story without resolution", "a type of rhyme scheme", "a poem written entirely in Latin"], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"In medias res\" (Latin for 'into the middle of things') describes starting a narrative in the middle of the action, rather than from the very beginning of the story's events.", "hint": "This Latin phrase describes a story that begins partway through the action, not at the chronological start."}, {"id": "sde94025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "9", "topic": "Literary Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G9-E4", "q": "What is a 'bildungsroman'?", "options": ["a type of formal letter", "a novel focused on the moral and psychological growth of its main character from youth to adulthood", "a poem with no fixed structure", "a play with only one character"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A bildungsroman is a novel focused on the moral, psychological, and intellectual growth of its protagonist, typically from youth into adulthood.", "hint": "This German-derived term describes a coming-of-age story tracing a character's development."}, {"id": "sde101001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read: 'The Renovation\n\nWhen Marisol's parents bought the old Trevino house, the real estate listing had used the word \"character\" seventeen times, which she now understood to be a euphemism for \"everything is slightly broken.\" Eight months into the renovation, she'd learned more about plumbing, structural load-bearing walls, and 1960s building codes than any sixteen-year-old should reasonably know.\n\nWhat she hadn't expected was the box.\n\nIt turned up wedged behind a wall cavity the electrician had opened up, water-damaged but mostly intact: a small collection of letters, photographs, and a child's drawing dated 1967. The letters were between two sisters, one of whom — according to the careful, looping handwriting — had lived in this exact house. Marisol read perhaps a dozen of them before her mother called her down for dinner, and found herself oddly reluctant to mention the discovery at the table.\n\nIt wasn't that the letters contained anything scandalous. They were, if anything, almost mundane — complaints about a difficult mother-in-law, updates about a vegetable garden's modest failures, a recurring joke about a neighbour's badly behaved dog. But there was something in their ordinariness that felt private in a way Marisol hadn't anticipated. These weren't dramatic secrets meant to be uncovered; they were just someone's actual life, never intended for a stranger's eyes fifty-odd years later.\n\nShe kept the box in her room for three weeks before mentioning it to anyone, turning the same question over without quite resolving it: did finding something accidentally, in a wall you happened to be renovating, grant you any right to it? The letters weren't valuable in any way she could articulate to her parents, who would likely see them as charming clutter at best. They mattered to her for a reason she struggled to explain even to herself — something about the strange intimacy of reading a stranger's grocery-list version of being alive, and the responsibility that seemed to come with that, however slight.\n\nEventually, she did what felt like the only reasonable thing: she found the sister's family — a phone number, eventually, through a genealogy website and a cousin three times removed — and mailed the box to an address in another state, keeping nothing but a single photograph of the garden, badly faded, that nobody on the other end particularly wanted back.'\n\nWhat does Marisol discover during the house renovation?", "options": ["a hidden room", "a box of letters, photographs, and a child's drawing from 1967", "a buried treasure chest", "an old family photo album belonging to her own family"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states she discovers 'a small collection of letters, photographs, and a child's drawing dated 1967'.", "hint": "Look at the second and third paragraphs for what was found in the wall cavity."}, {"id": "sde101002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does Marisol feel 'oddly reluctant to mention the discovery at the table'?", "options": ["she is afraid of getting in trouble", "the passage doesn't fully explain, but it's connected to the private, personal feeling the letters evoke", "she had already told her father privately", "she doesn't think the letters are interesting"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This reluctance seems connected to the sense of privacy and intimacy she feels about the letters, which the passage explores further in the following paragraph.", "hint": "Think about the feeling described in the next paragraph about the letters' 'ordinariness' feeling private."}, {"id": "sde101003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat makes the letters feel 'private' to Marisol, according to the fourth paragraph?", "options": ["they contain shocking, scandalous secrets", "their very ordinariness — mundane details of someone's actual life never meant for a stranger's eyes", "they are written in a language she doesn't understand", "they were locked in a safe"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states it was 'something in their ordinariness that felt private', describing the letters as containing someone's 'actual life, never intended for a stranger's eyes'.", "hint": "Look at the fourth paragraph for what specifically made the letters feel private, despite containing nothing scandalous."}, {"id": "sde101004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat central question does Marisol turn over for three weeks?", "options": ["whether to tell her parents about the renovation budget", "whether finding something accidentally grants any right to it", "whether to continue the house renovation at all", "whether the letters were forged"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage explicitly states her unresolved question: 'did finding something accidentally, in a wall you happened to be renovating, grant you any right to it?'", "hint": "Look at the fifth paragraph for the specific question stated."}, {"id": "sde101005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does Marisol ultimately decide to do with the letters?", "options": ["she keeps them permanently in her room", "she throws them away", "she finds the sister's family and mails the box to them, keeping only one photograph", "she sells them to a collector"], "answer": 2, "exp": "The passage states she 'found the sister's family... and mailed the box to an address in another state, keeping nothing but a single photograph'.", "hint": "Look at the final paragraph for her ultimate decision."}, {"id": "sde101006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the significance of the detail that the recipient family 'particularly wanted' nothing back, including the photograph Marisol kept?", "options": ["it shows the family was rude and ungrateful", "it subtly reinforces the theme that these small, personal artefacts hold meaning mainly for those who discover and reflect on them, not necessarily for distant descendants", "it proves the letters had no value at all", "it suggests the family had already seen the photograph before"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This detail subtly reinforces the story's exploration of how personal meaning in such artefacts can be more about the discoverer's reflection than about objective, universally recognised value.", "hint": "Think about what this detail suggests about where the 'meaning' of these objects actually comes from."}, {"id": "sde101007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'mundane' mean in the fourth paragraph?", "options": ["extremely exciting", "ordinary and unremarkable", "secretive and hidden", "valuable and rare"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Mundane\" means ordinary and unremarkable, fitting the description of the letters' everyday content (complaints, garden updates, a joke about a dog).", "hint": "Think about a word describing something very ordinary, lacking excitement or drama."}, {"id": "sde101008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the central theme explored in this passage?", "options": ["the practical challenges of home renovation", "the unexpected weight and responsibility of stumbling onto someone else's private, ordinary past", "the importance of always returning lost property immediately", "a mystery about who built the house originally"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage explores Marisol's reflection on the unexpected emotional and ethical weight of discovering someone else's private, ordinary life, and what responsibility (if any) that creates.", "hint": "Think about what Marisol spends most of her time reflecting on, beyond the simple facts of the discovery."}, {"id": "sde101009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read: 'On the Ethics of Algorithmic Recommendation\n\nEvery time a streaming platform suggests what to watch next, or a social media feed decides what to show you, an algorithm has made a quiet judgment about what will keep you engaged. For most of the history of media, this judgment was made by human editors, programmers, and curators. Today, it is made largely by systems trained to optimise for one primary metric: continued attention.\n\nThis shift raises a question that often goes unexamined amid more headline-grabbing debates about technology: what obligations, if any, do these recommendation systems have toward the wellbeing of the people using them, as opposed to simply their engagement? An algorithm that maximises watch time is not, by design, equivalent to one that maximises a user's considered satisfaction, let alone their broader wellbeing. These can align, but there is no guarantee that they will.\n\nSome technology companies have begun introducing wellbeing-oriented features — screen time reports, gentle reminders to take breaks — but these exist largely alongside, rather than within, the core recommendation systems themselves. The fundamental incentive structure, which rewards continued engagement above most other outcomes, remains largely unchanged beneath these surface-level additions.\n\nDefenders of current systems sometimes argue that users retain ultimate responsibility and agency over their own media consumption, and that companies should not be expected to act paternalistically on users' behalf. This argument carries genuine weight; there is something uncomfortable about ceding judgment over what is \"good for us\" to corporations with their own commercial interests. Yet this argument becomes harder to sustain when applied to systems explicitly engineered, often using considerable behavioural research, to exploit predictable patterns in human attention and impulse control. The notion of \"agency\" assumes a contest between roughly equal parties — a assumption that strains credibility when one party has access to vast behavioural data and sophisticated optimisation techniques, and the other does not.\n\nNone of this implies that algorithmic recommendation is inherently harmful, or that human curation was somehow free of its own commercial and editorial biases. It does suggest, however, that the ethical questions surrounding these systems deserve more sustained attention than they generally receive — not as a footnote to discussions of misinformation or screen time, but as a central question about what these systems are actually designed to optimise for, and on whose behalf.'\n\nWhat metric does the writer claim most modern recommendation algorithms primarily optimise for?", "options": ["user wellbeing", "continued attention/engagement", "factual accuracy", "financial cost to the user"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states these systems are 'trained to optimise for one primary metric: continued attention'.", "hint": "Look at the first paragraph for the specific metric mentioned."}, {"id": "sde101010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's main point in the second paragraph about engagement versus wellbeing?", "options": ["engagement and wellbeing are always exactly the same thing", "maximising engagement does not automatically equate to maximising a user's genuine wellbeing or satisfaction", "wellbeing has no real connection to technology", "algorithms should be banned entirely"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer argues that 'an algorithm that maximises watch time is not, by design, equivalent to one that maximises a user's considered satisfaction, let alone their broader wellbeing', noting these 'can align, but there is no guarantee'.", "hint": "Look at the second paragraph for the writer's specific point about the relationship between engagement and wellbeing."}, {"id": "sde101011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nAccording to the third paragraph, what limitation does the writer identify in current 'wellbeing-oriented features'?", "options": ["they don't exist at all", "they exist alongside the core recommendation systems, rather than changing the fundamental incentive structure itself", "they are too expensive for companies to implement", "they have completely solved the underlying problem"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states these features 'exist largely alongside, rather than within, the core recommendation systems', leaving 'the fundamental incentive structure... largely unchanged'.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for the specific limitation described."}, {"id": "sde101012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat counter-argument does the writer acknowledge in the fourth paragraph, before responding to it?", "options": ["that algorithms are too simple to cause any real harm", "that users retain ultimate responsibility and agency over their own media consumption", "that all algorithms should be made completely public", "that companies have no commercial interests at all"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer acknowledges the argument 'that users retain ultimate responsibility and agency over their own media consumption, and that companies should not be expected to act paternalistically'.", "hint": "Look at the start of the fourth paragraph for the specific counter-argument raised."}, {"id": "sde101013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhy does the writer argue this counter-argument 'becomes harder to sustain' in certain cases?", "options": ["because all algorithms are identical in their design", "because some systems are explicitly engineered, using behavioural research, to exploit predictable patterns in human attention and impulse control", "because users always have complete control regardless of system design", "because companies never use behavioural research"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer argues the counter-argument weakens 'when applied to systems explicitly engineered... to exploit predictable patterns in human attention and impulse control'.", "hint": "Look at the fourth paragraph for the specific reason the writer gives for this argument's weakness."}, {"id": "sde101014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'paternalistically' most likely mean in the fourth paragraph?", "options": ["acting like a typical father in a family setting", "acting in a controlling way on someone else's behalf, as if they cannot make their own decisions", "acting with extreme aggression", "acting with complete transparency"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Paternalistically\" describes acting in a controlling, protective way on someone else's behalf, often implying the other party is treated as incapable of deciding for themselves.", "hint": "Think about a word related to overly controlling, protective behaviour toward someone treated as less capable."}, {"id": "sde101015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's stated position in the final paragraph?", "options": ["algorithmic recommendation is inherently harmful and should be banned", "the ethical questions surrounding these systems deserve more sustained, central attention, rather than being treated as a minor footnote", "human curation was always completely unbiased and fair", "there are no real ethical questions worth considering here"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer concludes that 'the ethical questions surrounding these systems deserve more sustained attention than they generally receive... as a central question', while explicitly avoiding the claim that algorithms are 'inherently harmful'.", "hint": "Look at the final paragraph for the writer's carefully qualified concluding position."}, {"id": "sde101016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Interpreting Mood", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the writer's overall approach throughout this passage?", "options": ["a one-sided rant with no acknowledgment of opposing views", "a careful, qualified argument that acknowledges counter-arguments and avoids overstating its claims", "a purely factual, opinion-free summary with no argument at all", "an angry, emotionally charged condemnation of technology companies"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Throughout the passage, the writer raises counter-arguments, qualifies claims (e.g. 'none of this implies... is inherently harmful'), and avoids sweeping, unqualified conclusions, reflecting a careful, balanced argumentative approach.", "hint": "Think about how the writer handles opposing views and avoids making overly broad, unqualified claims."}, {"id": "sde101017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'ambivalence'?", "options": ["certainty", "mixed or conflicting feelings", "extreme anger", "complete indifference"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Mixed or conflicting feelings\" matches the meaning of 'ambivalence', describing being torn between two opposing views or emotions.", "hint": "Think of a word describing being pulled in two different emotional directions at once."}, {"id": "sde101018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'paternalistic'?", "options": ["controlling", "protective", "respecting of others' autonomy", "authoritative"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Respecting of others' autonomy\" is the opposite of 'paternalistic', which describes acting in an overly controlling way on someone else's behalf.", "hint": "Think of a word describing trusting someone to make their own decisions, rather than deciding for them."}, {"id": "sde101019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'sustained' (as in 'sustained attention')?", "options": ["brief", "ongoing and continuous", "interrupted", "forgotten"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Ongoing and continuous\" matches the meaning of 'sustained' in this context, describing something maintained over an extended period.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something kept going steadily over time."}, {"id": "sde101020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'mundane'?", "options": ["ordinary", "extraordinary", "boring", "routine"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Extraordinary\" is the opposite of 'mundane', which describes something ordinary and unremarkable.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something remarkable and far from ordinary."}, {"id": "sde101021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'articulate' (as in 'struggled to articulate')?", "options": ["to forget completely", "to express clearly in words", "to ignore deliberately", "to argue aggressively"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"To express clearly in words\" matches the meaning of 'articulate' as a verb, describing putting thoughts or feelings into clear language.", "hint": "Think of a word describing putting a feeling or idea into clear, well-formed words."}, {"id": "sde101022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'genuine' (as in 'genuine weight')?", "options": ["sincere", "authentic", "false", "real"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"False\" is the opposite of 'genuine', which describes something real and authentic.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something that only appears to be real, but isn't."}, {"id": "sde101023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'strains' (as in 'strains credibility')?", "options": ["strengthens", "tests to the point of difficulty or implausibility", "completely ignores", "easily supports"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Tests to the point of difficulty or implausibility\" matches the meaning of 'strains' in this context, describing pushing something close to breaking point.", "hint": "Think of a word describing pushing something close to its limit, making it hard to maintain."}, {"id": "sde101024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Which word is the opposite of 'considerable' (as in 'considerable behavioural research')?", "options": ["significant", "substantial", "negligible", "extensive"], "answer": 2, "exp": "\"Negligible\" is the opposite of 'considerable', which describes something large or significant in amount.", "hint": "Think of a word describing something so small it can practically be ignored."}, {"id": "sde101025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E1", "q": "Which word means almost the same as 'exploit' (as in 'exploit predictable patterns')?", "options": ["to ignore completely", "to take advantage of, often unfairly", "to repair or fix", "to celebrate"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"To take advantage of, often unfairly\" matches the meaning of 'exploit' in this context, describing using something (often a weakness) for one's own benefit.", "hint": "Think of a word describing using a pattern or weakness to one's own advantage, often unfairly."}, {"id": "sde102001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Essay Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "In a well-structured argumentative essay, what is the main purpose of the introduction's 'thesis statement'?", "options": ["to summarise every point that will be made in exhaustive detail", "to clearly state the essay's central argument or position", "to provide a complete list of sources used", "to ask a series of unrelated questions"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A thesis statement clearly states the essay's central argument or position, giving the reader a clear sense of what will be argued throughout.", "hint": "Think about the single sentence that tells the reader exactly what the essay will argue."}, {"id": "sde102002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Essay Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "What is a 'topic sentence' within a body paragraph of an argumentative essay?", "options": ["the very last sentence of the entire essay", "a sentence that introduces the main point or claim of that specific paragraph", "a sentence containing only statistics", "a sentence that has no connection to the essay's argument"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A topic sentence introduces the main point or claim of a specific paragraph, usually appearing near its beginning.", "hint": "Think about the sentence that tells the reader what this particular paragraph will be about."}, {"id": "sde102003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Essay Structure — Counter-Arguments", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Why is it generally considered good practice to address a counter-argument within an argumentative essay?", "options": ["it weakens the writer's own position", "it can strengthen the overall argument by showing the writer has considered other viewpoints and can respond to them", "counter-arguments should always be avoided entirely", "it is only relevant in formal debates, not essays"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Addressing a counter-argument shows the writer has considered other viewpoints, which can strengthen the overall argument by demonstrating a more thorough, credible analysis.", "hint": "Think about how acknowledging an opposing view, then responding to it, can make an argument seem more credible."}, {"id": "sde102004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Essay Structure — Counter-Arguments", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which best describes 'concession' in argumentative writing?", "options": ["completely abandoning one's own argument", "acknowledging a valid point made by the opposing side, while still maintaining one's overall position", "ignoring all opposing viewpoints entirely", "a technique used only in persuasive speeches, never in essays"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A concession acknowledges a valid point from the opposing side, while the writer still maintains their overall position, often before responding with a rebuttal.", "hint": "Think about partially agreeing with an opposing point, without fully abandoning your own argument."}, {"id": "sde102005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Essay Structure — Counter-Arguments", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "What is the purpose of a 'rebuttal' following a concession in an argumentative essay?", "options": ["to fully agree with the opposing argument", "to respond to and counter the concern raised, reinforcing the writer's original position", "to introduce a completely new, unrelated topic", "rebuttals serve no real purpose in essay writing"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A rebuttal responds to and counters a concern raised by the opposing view, reinforcing the writer's original position after acknowledging that concern.", "hint": "Think about responding directly to the concession just made, to bring the argument back to your side."}, {"id": "sde102006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Logical Fallacies", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates an example of a logical fallacy known as a 'slippery slope' argument?", "options": ["If we allow students to redo this assignment, soon no one will ever complete assignments properly, and academic standards will completely collapse.", "Some students may benefit from redoing this assignment.", "The teacher decided to allow one student to redo the assignment.", "Most students complete their assignments on time."], "answer": 0, "exp": "This is a slippery slope fallacy, suggesting an extreme, exaggerated chain of consequences will inevitably follow from a single, relatively minor decision.", "hint": "Look for the option suggesting one small action will inevitably lead to an extreme, exaggerated outcome."}, {"id": "sde102007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Logical Fallacies", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates an 'ad hominem' fallacy?", "options": ["Her argument about the policy is flawed because she has never personally been affected by it, so we can dismiss everything she says.", "The policy has both benefits and drawbacks.", "The policy was introduced last year.", "Several experts have reviewed the policy's effects."], "answer": 0, "exp": "An ad hominem fallacy attacks the person making an argument, rather than addressing the actual argument itself — dismissing her view based on her personal circumstances rather than the argument's content.", "hint": "Look for the option that attacks the person, rather than addressing the actual substance of their argument."}, {"id": "sde102008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Logical Fallacies", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates a 'false dichotomy' (false dilemma) fallacy?", "options": ["Either we ban this completely, or we're saying we don't care about safety at all — there's no middle ground.", "There are several possible approaches to this issue.", "Some people support the ban, while others oppose it.", "The committee will vote on the proposal next week."], "answer": 0, "exp": "A false dichotomy presents only two extreme options as if they were the only possibilities, ignoring any potential middle ground or alternative approaches.", "hint": "Look for the option that presents only two extreme choices, ignoring any other possibilities."}, {"id": "sde102009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Grammar — Subjunctive Mood", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses the subjunctive mood in a formal recommendation?", "options": ["I recommend that he attends the meeting.", "I recommend that he attend the meeting.", "I recommend that he is attending the meeting.", "I recommend that he will attend the meeting."], "answer": 1, "exp": "In formal recommendations, the subjunctive mood uses the base form of the verb regardless of subject: \"I recommend that he attend the meeting\" (not 'attends').", "hint": "In formal recommendations using 'that', the verb typically takes its base form, not the usual third-person form."}, {"id": "sde102010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Grammar — Nominalisation", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates correct use of a nominalisation (turning a verb into a noun) for formal academic tone?", "options": ["The committee decided to investigate the issue.", "The committee's investigation of the issue began promptly.", "The committee will look into the issue.", "The committee investigated the issue quickly."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Investigation\" is a nominalisation of the verb 'investigate', commonly used in formal academic writing to create a more objective, formal tone.", "hint": "Look for the sentence that turns an action (a verb) into a thing (a noun)."}, {"id": "sde102011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Grammar — Sentence Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses a complex sentence with embedded clauses for sophisticated argumentation?", "options": ["The policy failed. It was poorly designed. Few people supported it.", "The policy, which was poorly designed from the outset, failed largely because so few people supported it.", "The policy failed and it was poorly designed and few people supported it.", "The policy failed, poorly designed, few people, supported it."], "answer": 1, "exp": "This sentence embeds a relative clause ('which was poorly designed from the outset') and a causal clause ('because so few people supported it') into one cohesive, sophisticated sentence.", "hint": "Look for the sentence that combines multiple related ideas smoothly into one complex sentence, rather than several short ones."}, {"id": "sde102012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Academic Writing — Hedging", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which best describes the purpose of a 'hedge' in academic or argumentative writing, such as 'it could be argued that' or 'this suggests'?", "options": ["to make the writer's claims sound more aggressive", "to soften a claim, acknowledging it may not be absolutely certain, while still making the point", "hedges are never used in formal academic writing", "to confuse the reader deliberately"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A hedge softens a claim, acknowledging some degree of uncertainty, while still allowing the writer to make their point — common in careful academic or argumentative writing.", "hint": "Think about language that makes a claim sound appropriately cautious, rather than absolutely certain."}, {"id": "sde102013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Academic Writing — Hedging", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence uses a hedge appropriately in academic writing?", "options": ["This proves conclusively that the policy is a complete failure.", "This suggests that the policy may not be achieving its intended outcomes.", "The policy is definitely a failure, without question.", "Everyone agrees the policy has completely failed."], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"This suggests that... may not be\" appropriately hedges the claim, acknowledging some uncertainty rather than overstating the case with absolute certainty.", "hint": "Look for language that allows room for some uncertainty, rather than claiming absolute, unqualified certainty."}, {"id": "sde102014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Logical Fallacies", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates an appeal to popularity (bandwagon) fallacy?", "options": ["Most people support this policy, so it must be the correct approach.", "Experts have studied this policy extensively.", "The policy has both supporters and critics.", "The policy was implemented last year."], "answer": 0, "exp": "This is a bandwagon fallacy, assuming something must be correct simply because many people believe or support it, rather than evaluating the argument's actual merits.", "hint": "Look for the option that argues something must be true or correct simply because it's popular."}, {"id": "sde102015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Logical Fallacies", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates a 'hasty generalisation' fallacy?", "options": ["I met two rude people from that city, so everyone from there must be rude.", "Some people from that city were unfriendly when I visited.", "Cities often have diverse populations with varied personalities.", "I haven't visited that city before."], "answer": 0, "exp": "This is a hasty generalisation, drawing a broad conclusion about an entire group based on a very small, potentially unrepresentative sample.", "hint": "Look for the option that draws a sweeping conclusion about a large group, based on very limited evidence."}, {"id": "sde102016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Punctuation — Semicolons", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates effective use of a semicolon to connect two closely related independent clauses in formal writing?", "options": ["The evidence was compelling; the jury reached a verdict quickly.", "The evidence was compelling, the jury reached a verdict quickly.", "The evidence was compelling the jury reached a verdict quickly.", "The evidence; was compelling, the jury reached a verdict; quickly."], "answer": 0, "exp": "The semicolon correctly joins two closely related independent clauses without needing a coordinating conjunction: \"The evidence was compelling; the jury reached a verdict quickly.\"", "hint": "A semicolon should join two complete, closely related sentences without a comma alone or a missing conjunction."}, {"id": "sde102017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Essay Structure", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which best describes an effective concluding paragraph in an argumentative essay?", "options": ["it should introduce several brand new arguments not previously mentioned", "it should restate the thesis in fresh language and consider the argument's broader significance, without simply repeating the introduction word-for-word", "it should be the shortest paragraph, with no real content", "it should apologise for any weaknesses in the argument"], "answer": 1, "exp": "An effective conclusion restates the thesis using fresh language and considers the argument's broader significance, rather than simply repeating the introduction.", "hint": "Think about adding something new in how the argument is framed, rather than just copying the introduction."}, {"id": "sde102018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Logical Fallacies", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates a straw man fallacy?", "options": ["My opponent wants better regulation, but apparently they want to ban this activity completely, which is clearly extreme and unworkable.", "My opponent supports better regulation of this activity.", "Regulation can take many different forms.", "Some regulations have proven effective in similar contexts."], "answer": 0, "exp": "This is a straw man fallacy, misrepresenting the opponent's actual, more moderate position ('better regulation') as something more extreme ('ban completely') in order to attack it more easily.", "hint": "Look for the option that exaggerates or distorts an opponent's actual position, making it easier to criticise."}, {"id": "sde102019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Essay Structure — Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates an appropriate use of a rhetorical question to open an argumentative essay?", "options": ["What is the capital of France?", "How much longer can we ignore the clear evidence of this growing crisis?", "Did you have a good breakfast this morning?", "What time does the library close on Sundays?"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This rhetorical question is designed to provoke thought about the essay's central issue, drawing the reader in, rather than seeking a literal factual answer.", "hint": "Look for the question connected to a serious, debatable issue, rather than a simple factual question."}, {"id": "sde102020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Essay Structure — Cohesion", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which best describes the function of a 'signpost' phrase, such as 'furthermore' or 'in contrast', within an argumentative essay?", "options": ["it has no real function and can be removed without consequence", "it helps guide the reader through the logical structure and flow of the argument", "it is only used in casual, informal writing", "it always indicates the essay is concluding"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Signpost phrases like 'furthermore' or 'in contrast' help guide the reader through the logical structure of the argument, signalling how each point relates to what came before.", "hint": "Think about words that help a reader understand whether a new point is building on, or contrasting with, the previous one."}, {"id": "sde102021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Logical Fallacies", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates a circular argument (begging the question) fallacy?", "options": ["This law is just, because it is the law, and laws are just by definition.", "This law was passed by the parliament.", "Some people disagree with this particular law.", "The law has been in effect for several years."], "answer": 0, "exp": "This is a circular argument, where the conclusion ('this law is just') is essentially restated as its own justification ('laws are just by definition'), without providing independent supporting evidence.", "hint": "Look for the option where the argument's conclusion is essentially just restated as the reason supporting it."}, {"id": "sde102022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Essay Structure — Vocabulary", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which best describes the purpose of using precise, topic-specific vocabulary in an argumentative essay, rather than vague, general terms?", "options": ["it makes the essay more difficult to understand for no real benefit", "it demonstrates a stronger command of the subject and can make the argument more persuasive and credible", "precise vocabulary should always be avoided in essays", "vague vocabulary is always preferable in formal writing"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Precise, topic-specific vocabulary demonstrates a stronger command of the subject matter, which can make an argument appear more credible and persuasive to the reader.", "hint": "Think about how using exact, specific terms (rather than vague ones) might affect how credible an argument seems."}, {"id": "sde102023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Punctuation — Em Dashes", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence correctly uses an em dash to add emphasis or an abrupt interruption?", "options": ["The decision — and this surprised everyone — was reversed within a week.", "The decision and, this surprised everyone, was reversed within — a week.", "The decision—and this surprised everyone—was reversed, within a week.", "The — decision and this surprised everyone was reversed within a week."], "answer": 0, "exp": "The em dash correctly sets off the interrupting phrase 'and this surprised everyone' for emphasis, while the rest of the sentence remains grammatically intact.", "hint": "The interrupting phrase should be clearly set off by dashes on both sides, without disrupting the rest of the sentence's grammar."}, {"id": "sde102024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Logical Fallacies", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which best describes a 'false cause' (post hoc) fallacy?", "options": ["assuming that because one event followed another, the first event must have caused the second", "correctly identifying a clear, well-evidenced cause and effect relationship", "acknowledging that correlation does not always imply causation", "using a relevant statistic to support an argument"], "answer": 0, "exp": "A false cause (post hoc) fallacy assumes that because one event happened before another, the first must have caused the second, without sufficient evidence for this causal link.", "hint": "Think about wrongly assuming that simply happening first means an event caused what came after it."}, {"id": "sde102025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Logical Fallacies", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E2", "q": "Which sentence best demonstrates an appeal to authority used appropriately, rather than fallaciously?", "options": ["My friend says this medical treatment works, so it must be effective.", "According to multiple peer-reviewed studies published by medical researchers, this treatment has shown measurable benefits.", "Everyone knows this treatment works.", "A celebrity recommended this treatment on social media."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Citing peer-reviewed studies from qualified medical researchers is an appropriate use of authority, relying on relevant expertise and evidence, unlike the other options which rely on irrelevant or unverified sources.", "hint": "Look for the option that cites a genuinely relevant, credible, and evidence-based source."}, {"id": "sde103001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Satire", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "What is 'satire' in literature?", "options": ["a serious, formal style with no humour", "a genre that uses humour, irony, or exaggeration to criticise or mock a subject, often social or political", "a type of poem with a strict rhyme scheme", "a factual report with no creative elements"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Satire uses humour, irony, or exaggeration to criticise or mock a subject, often targeting social, political, or human folly.", "hint": "Think about a genre that uses comedy or exaggeration as a tool for criticism, rather than just entertainment."}, {"id": "sde103002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Irony", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'dramatic irony'?", "options": ["when a character says something accidentally funny", "when the audience knows something a character does not, creating tension or insight", "when a story has an unexpected happy ending", "when a character speaks in an overly dramatic tone"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Dramatic irony occurs when the audience or reader knows something important that a character does not, often creating tension or a sense of foreboding.", "hint": "Think about the audience being 'one step ahead' of a character in their understanding of the situation."}, {"id": "sde103003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Irony", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'situational irony'?", "options": ["when the outcome of a situation is the opposite of what was expected", "when a character speaks sarcastically", "when the audience and characters share exactly the same knowledge", "when a story is told entirely out of order"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Situational irony occurs when the actual outcome of a situation is strikingly different from, or the opposite of, what was expected.", "hint": "Think about an outcome that surprises everyone because it's the opposite of what 'should' have happened."}, {"id": "sde103004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Irony", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'verbal irony'?", "options": ["when a character's words mean the literal opposite of, or something quite different from, their intended meaning", "when two characters speak the same language", "when dialogue is written entirely in capital letters", "when a narrator never speaks directly to the reader"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Verbal irony occurs when someone says something that means the opposite of, or something quite different from, what they actually intend, often for sarcastic or humorous effect.", "hint": "Think about saying one thing while clearly meaning something else, often sarcastically."}, {"id": "sde103005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Comparative Analysis", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "In comparative analysis, what does it mean to compare the 'tone' of two texts?", "options": ["comparing how loudly each text would be read aloud", "comparing the overall attitude or feeling conveyed by each writer toward their subject", "comparing only the length of each text", "comparing the font used in each text's publication"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Comparing tone involves examining the overall attitude or feeling each writer conveys toward their subject — such as serious, humorous, critical, or sympathetic.", "hint": "Think about the overall emotional 'colour' or attitude each writer brings to their subject."}, {"id": "sde103006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Comparative Analysis", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "When comparing two persuasive texts on the same topic, why might examining each writer's choice of evidence be useful?", "options": ["it reveals nothing meaningful about either text", "it can reveal differing priorities, assumptions, or intended audiences between the two writers", "evidence is identical in all persuasive texts", "comparing evidence is only relevant in scientific writing, not persuasive writing"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Examining each writer's choice of evidence (such as statistics, anecdotes, or expert opinions) can reveal differing priorities, assumptions, or intended audiences between the two texts.", "hint": "Think about what the TYPE of evidence chosen might reveal about each writer's approach or audience."}, {"id": "sde103007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Allegory", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes an 'allegory' in literature?", "options": ["a short poem with no deeper meaning", "a narrative in which characters, events, or settings represent broader ideas or moral, political, or social concepts", "a factual historical account", "a story with no characters at all"], "answer": 1, "exp": "An allegory is a narrative where characters, events, or settings represent broader ideas or concepts, often moral, political, or social in nature.", "hint": "Think about a story that works on two levels: a literal surface story, and a deeper, symbolic meaning."}, {"id": "sde103008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Rhetorical Appeals", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "What is 'pathos' as a persuasive or rhetorical appeal?", "options": ["an appeal based on logic and evidence", "an appeal to the audience's emotions", "an appeal based on the speaker's credibility or authority", "an appeal that uses only statistics"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Pathos is a rhetorical appeal that targets the audience's emotions, aiming to persuade through feelings rather than pure logic or authority.", "hint": "Think about the Greek root related to 'feeling' or 'suffering', as in 'sympathy' or 'empathy'."}, {"id": "sde103009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Rhetorical Appeals", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "What is 'logos' as a persuasive or rhetorical appeal?", "options": ["an appeal to emotion", "an appeal based on logic, reasoning, and evidence", "an appeal based purely on the speaker's reputation", "an appeal that relies entirely on humour"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Logos is a rhetorical appeal based on logic, reasoning, and evidence, aiming to persuade through rational argument.", "hint": "Think about the Greek root related to 'logic' or 'reason'."}, {"id": "sde103010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Rhetorical Appeals", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "What is 'ethos' as a persuasive or rhetorical appeal?", "options": ["an appeal to logic only", "an appeal based on the speaker's credibility, character, or authority", "an appeal based entirely on emotion", "an appeal that uses only statistics"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Ethos is a rhetorical appeal based on the speaker's credibility, character, or perceived authority, aiming to persuade by establishing trust.", "hint": "Think about the Greek root related to 'character' or 'ethics'."}, {"id": "sde103011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'foreshadowing' as a literary device?", "options": ["describing events that have already happened in great detail", "hinting at events that will occur later in the narrative", "using extremely long, complex sentences", "writing a story with no plot at all"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Foreshadowing is a literary device where a writer hints at events that will occur later in the narrative, often creating tension or anticipation.", "hint": "Think about a subtle clue planted early in a story, hinting at something that hasn't happened yet."}, {"id": "sde103012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'in medias res' as a narrative technique?", "options": ["beginning a story right in the middle of the action, rather than at the very start of events", "ending a story without any resolution", "writing a story entirely in the past tense", "using only dialogue throughout an entire story"], "answer": 0, "exp": "\"In medias res\" (Latin for 'into the middle of things') describes beginning a narrative in the middle of the action, rather than chronologically from the very start.", "hint": "Think about a story that starts with an exciting event, before explaining how the characters got there."}, {"id": "sde103013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Comparative Analysis", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "When comparing the structure of two texts, what might differing paragraph lengths and sentence complexity reveal about each writer's intended audience?", "options": ["nothing meaningful at all", "shorter, simpler structures often suggest a broader or younger audience, while longer, complex structures may suggest a more specialised or academic audience", "sentence length has no connection to audience at all", "all texts are written for exactly the same audience regardless of structure"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Shorter, simpler sentence and paragraph structures often suggest a broader or younger intended audience, while longer, more complex structures may suggest a more specialised or academic audience.", "hint": "Think about how the complexity of writing might be adjusted depending on who the writer expects to be reading it."}, {"id": "sde103014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'understatement' as a literary or rhetorical device?", "options": ["deliberately exaggerating something far beyond its actual significance", "deliberately representing something as less significant or serious than it actually is, often for ironic or humorous effect", "stating something with complete neutrality and no particular effect", "always speaking as loudly as possible"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Understatement deliberately represents something as less significant than it actually is, often used for ironic, humorous, or restrained emotional effect.", "hint": "Think about deliberately downplaying something serious, often creating an ironic or darkly humorous effect."}, {"id": "sde103015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which sentence demonstrates understatement?", "options": ["The hurricane caused unimaginable, catastrophic devastation across the entire region.", "After losing both his arms in the accident, he remarked that it was 'a bit of a setback'.", "The team celebrated wildly after their unexpected victory.", "The weather forecast predicted clear skies for the entire week."], "answer": 1, "exp": "Describing losing both arms as 'a bit of a setback' is a striking example of understatement, deliberately downplaying something extremely serious.", "hint": "Look for the option describing something genuinely serious in deliberately mild, downplayed language."}, {"id": "sde103016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Satire", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'satire' using exaggeration, as commonly seen in political cartoons?", "options": ["depicting a subject with complete photographic realism", "exaggerating specific features or behaviours of a subject to highlight and criticise particular flaws or absurdities", "avoiding any criticism of public figures entirely", "using only neutral, factual captions with no visual exaggeration"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Satirical exaggeration, common in political cartoons, deliberately overstates specific features or behaviours to highlight and criticise particular flaws or absurdities in the subject.", "hint": "Think about how a cartoonist might deliberately distort certain features to make a critical point."}, {"id": "sde103017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Comparative Analysis — Spoken Texts", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "When analysing a persuasive speech, why might examining the speaker's use of pacing and repetition be useful, alongside the actual words used?", "options": ["pacing and repetition have no real persuasive effect", "these techniques can build emotional intensity and emphasis, working alongside the literal content to strengthen the persuasive effect", "only the literal meaning of words ever matters in a speech", "pacing and repetition are only relevant in written texts, not spoken ones"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Pacing and repetition can build emotional intensity and emphasis in a spoken text, working alongside the literal content of the words to strengthen the overall persuasive effect.", "hint": "Think about how the rhythm and repeated structure of spoken language can add to its impact, beyond just the words themselves."}, {"id": "sde103018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes a 'frame narrative' (a story within a story)?", "options": ["a story with no characters", "a narrative structure where one story contains, or 'frames', another story told within it", "a story told entirely through dialogue", "a story with no clear beginning or end"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A frame narrative is a structure where one outer story contains, or 'frames', another story told within it, often by a character recounting events to another character.", "hint": "Think about a story where a character tells another story, nested inside the main narrative."}, {"id": "sde103019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'juxtaposition' as a literary device, when comparing two texts?", "options": ["placing two contrasting ideas, characters, or images close together to highlight their differences", "describing only one idea throughout an entire text", "always placing similar ideas together to emphasise similarity", "a technique used only in non-fiction writing"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Juxtaposition places two contrasting ideas, characters, or images close together, highlighting their differences through direct comparison.", "hint": "Think about placing two very different things side by side, so the contrast between them becomes obvious."}, {"id": "sde103020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Comparative Analysis — Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best explains why comparing the historical or cultural CONTEXT of two texts can deepen analysis?", "options": ["context never affects how a text should be interpreted", "understanding the time, place, and circumstances in which each text was written can reveal why writers made certain choices or held certain assumptions", "context is only relevant for ancient texts, not modern ones", "comparing context is the same as comparing plot"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Understanding the historical or cultural context surrounding a text's creation can reveal why a writer made certain choices, held certain assumptions, or addressed particular concerns relevant to their time.", "hint": "Think about how knowing WHEN and WHERE a text was written might explain certain choices the writer made."}, {"id": "sde103021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes a 'motif' that recurs across multiple texts being compared?", "options": ["a single, one-time image with no broader significance", "a recurring image, symbol, or idea that appears across different points in a text, or even across multiple texts, often reinforcing a shared theme", "a type of punctuation mark", "a structural feature only found in poetry"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A motif is a recurring image, symbol, or idea, which can reinforce a theme within a single text, or be compared across multiple texts addressing similar concerns.", "hint": "Think about an image or idea that keeps reappearing, possibly across more than one text being studied."}, {"id": "sde103022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'black comedy' (dark humour) as a literary technique?", "options": ["humour that deals with serious, taboo, or tragic subjects in a way that provokes uneasy laughter", "humour that only ever discusses cheerful, light topics", "a complete absence of any comedic elements", "humour used exclusively in children's literature"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Black comedy (dark humour) deals with serious, taboo, or tragic subjects in a way that provokes uneasy or uncomfortable laughter, often used for social or psychological commentary.", "hint": "Think about humour that finds something to laugh at within an otherwise serious or tragic subject."}, {"id": "sde103023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Comparative Analysis — Imagery", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "When comparing two writers' use of imagery, what might a focus on harsh, jagged sensory descriptions (as opposed to soft, flowing ones) suggest about each writer's intended mood?", "options": ["imagery has no connection to mood at all", "harsh, jagged imagery often suggests tension, conflict, or unease, while soft, flowing imagery often suggests calm or harmony", "both types of imagery always create exactly the same mood", "imagery only matters in poetry, never in prose"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Harsh, jagged sensory descriptions often suggest tension, conflict, or unease, while soft, flowing imagery often suggests calm or harmony, giving clues about each writer's intended mood.", "hint": "Think about how the QUALITY of descriptive language (harsh versus soft) might affect the feeling it creates in the reader."}, {"id": "sde103024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes an 'unreliable narrator'?", "options": ["a narrator whose credibility is compromised, whether through bias, limited knowledge, or deliberate deception, requiring readers to question their account", "a narrator who always tells the complete, objective truth", "a narrator who never speaks in the first person", "a narrator only found in non-fiction writing"], "answer": 0, "exp": "An unreliable narrator's credibility is compromised in some way, whether through personal bias, limited knowledge, or deliberate deception, requiring readers to critically question their account of events.", "hint": "Think about a narrator whose version of events you might need to question, rather than simply trust."}, {"id": "sde103025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E3", "q": "Which best describes 'pathetic fallacy' as a literary device?", "options": ["attributing human emotions to nature or the environment, often to reflect a character's inner state", "a logical error in an argument", "a type of formal apology within a text", "a narrative told entirely without any descriptive language"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Pathetic fallacy attributes human emotions to nature or the environment (such as a 'gloomy sky' or 'angry sea'), often used to reflect or amplify a character's inner emotional state.", "hint": "Think about weather or nature being described as if it shared a character's mood."}, {"id": "sde104001", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read: 'Why We Should Reconsider the Four-Day School Week\n\nFor more than a century, the five-day school week has been treated as an unquestioned fixture of education, as natural and immovable as the existence of summer holidays. Yet a small but growing number of schools, both in Australia and internationally, have begun trialling a four-day model — and the results deserve more serious attention than they have so far received.\n\nThe most common objection is immediate and intuitive: less time in school must surely mean less learning. This assumes, however, that classroom hours translate directly and proportionally into educational outcomes — an assumption that several trials have begun to complicate. Schools adopting a four-day week typically extend each remaining day, preserving most or all instructional hours rather than simply cutting them. Early results from several such trials suggest that student engagement and teacher retention improve, while academic outcomes remain largely stable rather than declining.\n\nCritics raise a fair point about working families: a missing school day creates genuine logistical and financial strain for parents who cannot simply rearrange their own work schedules to match. This is not a trivial concern, and any serious four-day proposal must address it directly, whether through subsidised care programs on the off day or partnerships with community organisations. Dismissing the four-day model on this basis alone, however, mistakes a solvable logistical problem for a fundamental flaw in the underlying idea.\n\nA subtler argument concerns teacher wellbeing and retention, an issue rarely placed at the centre of these debates despite its obvious downstream importance for students. Teacher burnout and attrition have reached levels that many education systems openly acknowledge as a crisis, and the four-day model — even accounting for longer remaining days — appears in early data to meaningfully reduce burnout indicators among trial participants. A school that cannot retain experienced, well-supported teachers is unlikely to serve its students well regardless of how many days it operates.\n\nNone of this constitutes definitive proof that every school should adopt a four-day model immediately. The trials remain small, relatively recent, and not yet replicated at sufficient scale to draw firm conclusions. What they do suggest is that an assumption many of us have never seriously questioned — that more days in the classroom straightforwardly means better outcomes — deserves rather more scrutiny than the reflexive dismissal it usually receives.'\n\nWhat assumption does the writer challenge in the second paragraph?", "options": ["that students always prefer shorter school weeks", "that classroom hours translate directly and proportionally into educational outcomes", "that teachers are always overworked", "that four-day school weeks are illegal"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer explicitly challenges 'an assumption... that classroom hours translate directly and proportionally into educational outcomes'.", "hint": "Look at the second paragraph for the specific assumption being questioned."}, {"id": "sde104002", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nHow do schools adopting a four-day week typically address the reduction in days, according to the passage?", "options": ["they simply cut total instructional hours", "they extend each remaining day, preserving most or all instructional hours", "they eliminate all extracurricular activities", "they reduce the number of subjects taught"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states these schools 'typically extend each remaining day, preserving most or all instructional hours rather than simply cutting them'.", "hint": "Look at the second paragraph for how schools compensate for the missing day."}, {"id": "sde104003", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat concern about working families does the writer acknowledge in the third paragraph?", "options": ["families cannot afford school fees", "a missing school day creates genuine logistical and financial strain for parents", "families disagree with the entire concept of school", "working families have no children in school"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer acknowledges this creates 'genuine logistical and financial strain for parents who cannot simply rearrange their own work schedules'.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for the specific concern raised about working families."}, {"id": "sde104004", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the writer suggest in response to this concern about working families?", "options": ["the concern should be completely dismissed as irrelevant", "any serious proposal must address it directly, such as through subsidised care programs", "working families should simply quit their jobs", "the four-day model should never be implemented anywhere"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The writer states 'any serious four-day proposal must address it directly, whether through subsidised care programs... or partnerships with community organisations'.", "hint": "Look at the third paragraph for the writer's suggested solution to this concern."}, {"id": "sde104005", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat issue does the fourth paragraph argue is 'rarely placed at the centre of these debates', despite its importance?", "options": ["school transport logistics", "teacher wellbeing and retention", "the cost of textbooks", "the length of school holidays"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The passage states 'teacher wellbeing and retention, an issue rarely placed at the centre of these debates despite its obvious downstream importance for students'.", "hint": "Look at the start of the fourth paragraph for this specific issue."}, {"id": "sde104006", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat is the writer's overall conclusion in the final paragraph?", "options": ["every school should immediately adopt a four-day model", "the trials prove definitively that four-day weeks always work", "the underlying assumption about classroom days deserves more scrutiny, though the evidence isn't yet conclusive", "four-day school weeks have been proven to be a complete failure"], "answer": 2, "exp": "The writer concludes that 'an assumption... deserves rather more scrutiny', while explicitly noting 'none of this constitutes definitive proof' and that trials remain small and not yet replicated at scale.", "hint": "Look at the final paragraph for the writer's carefully qualified conclusion."}, {"id": "sde104007", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Vocabulary in Context", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhat does the word 'reflexive' mean in the final sentence ('the reflexive dismissal it usually receives')?", "options": ["carefully considered after lengthy debate", "automatic and unthinking, without careful consideration", "extremely rare and unusual", "based on strong scientific evidence"], "answer": 1, "exp": "\"Reflexive\" means automatic and unthinking, similar to a reflex action — suggesting the dismissal of this idea often happens without careful consideration.", "hint": "Think about a word related to 'reflex' — an automatic, almost involuntary reaction."}, {"id": "sde104008", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Persuasive Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same passage.\n\nWhich best describes the persuasive strategy the writer uses throughout this passage?", "options": ["dismissing all opposing concerns without any acknowledgment", "presenting a carefully qualified case, acknowledging genuine concerns while arguing the issue deserves more serious consideration", "using purely emotional appeals with no evidence at all", "refusing to take any position on the issue"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Throughout the passage, the writer acknowledges genuine concerns (working families, limited trial evidence) while still arguing the underlying issue deserves more serious consideration than it typically receives.", "hint": "Think about how the writer balances acknowledging real concerns with still making a clear argument."}, {"id": "sde104009", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literal Comprehension", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read: 'Inheritance\n\nMy grandfather's hands, in the one photograph\nthat survived the move, the flood, the decade\nnobody photographed anything —\nthick-knuckled, holding a wrench\nthe way some men hold a child,\ncareful and absent-minded at once.\n\nI never knew him well enough\nto inherit anything specific —\nno trade, no specific skill passed down\nhand to hand across a workbench.\nAnd yet, my own hands, lately,\ndoing something as ordinary as fixing a hinge,\nmove in a way I don't recognise as mine,\na kind of muscle memory\nfor a memory I don't actually have.\n\nIs this what inheritance means,\nonce you strip away the house, the money,\nthe things you can argue over in a lawyer's office?\nSome residue of a person\nsettling, uninvited, into your own gestures,\nyour own quiet competence with tools\nyou were never taught to use\nby the man whose hands you apparently borrowed\nwithout either of you agreeing to the loan.\n\nI don't believe in ghosts, particularly.\nBut I believe, now, in this —\nthat something of a person\ncan survive in the angle of a wrist,\nthe unconscious choice\nto hold a tool a particular way,\npassed down through no mechanism\nanyone has ever managed to properly explain.'\n\nWhat does the speaker say they 'never knew well enough' to directly inherit?", "options": ["any money or property", "a trade or specific skill passed down hand to hand", "their grandfather's name", "a house"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem states 'I never knew him well enough to inherit anything specific — no trade, no specific skill passed down hand to hand across a workbench'.", "hint": "Look at the second stanza for what the speaker says they didn't directly inherit."}, {"id": "sde104010", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat surprising observation does the speaker make about their own hands in the second stanza?", "options": ["their hands are identical in appearance to their grandfather's", "their hands move in an unfamiliar way while doing ordinary tasks, as if remembering something the speaker never actually learned", "their hands are unable to do any practical tasks", "their hands have been injured in an accident"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The speaker describes their hands moving 'in a way I don't recognise as mine, a kind of muscle memory for a memory I don't actually have'.", "hint": "Look at the end of the second stanza for this specific, unexpected observation."}, {"id": "sde104011", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nIn the third stanza, what does the speaker suggest 'inheritance' might really mean, beyond material possessions?", "options": ["inheritance is purely about legal documents and money", "some intangible trace of a person settling into one's own unconscious gestures and habits", "inheritance always requires direct teaching", "inheritance is entirely imaginary and meaningless"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The speaker suggests inheritance might involve 'some residue of a person settling, uninvited, into your own gestures', beyond 'the house, the money'.", "hint": "Look at the third stanza for what the speaker proposes inheritance might really consist of, beyond material things."}, {"id": "sde104012", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat is the effect of the phrase 'without either of you agreeing to the loan' at the end of the third stanza?", "options": ["it suggests a formal legal contract was involved", "it extends the financial metaphor (borrowing/loan) in an unexpected, slightly humorous way to describe an involuntary, unspoken inheritance", "it suggests the grandfather was angry about the inheritance", "it has no real literary effect"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This phrase extends the metaphor of 'borrowing' hands into financial language ('loan', 'agreeing'), creating a slightly wry, unexpected way of describing something entirely involuntary and unspoken.", "hint": "Think about how describing an unconscious inheritance using financial language ('loan', 'agreeing') creates an interesting, slightly unexpected effect."}, {"id": "sde104013", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Inference", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhat does the speaker mean by saying 'I don't believe in ghosts, particularly. / But I believe, now, in this' in the final stanza?", "options": ["the speaker has become religious", "the speaker is drawing a deliberate contrast between supernatural belief and a more grounded, but still mysterious, sense of inherited trace or memory", "the speaker is afraid of ghosts", "the speaker no longer believes in their grandfather's existence"], "answer": 1, "exp": "This contrast positions the speaker's experience as something real and felt, yet still mysterious and hard to explain — distinct from supernatural belief, but just as difficult to fully account for.", "hint": "Think about why the speaker specifically distances this experience from 'ghosts', while still describing something they find hard to fully explain."}, {"id": "sde104014", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhich literary device is most prominent in the poem's central conceit of inherited physical gestures?", "options": ["onomatopoeia", "an extended metaphor exploring inheritance as something physical and unconscious, rather than purely material", "alliteration", "a strict, traditional rhyme scheme"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem develops an extended metaphor throughout, exploring 'inheritance' as something physical and unconscious (gestures, muscle memory) rather than purely material (money, property).", "hint": "Think about the central idea that runs throughout the entire poem, developed and explored across multiple stanzas."}, {"id": "sde104015", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Writer's Craft", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhich best describes the overall structure of the poem, in terms of free verse versus strict form?", "options": ["the poem follows a strict, traditional rhyme scheme and fixed metre throughout", "the poem is written in free verse, without a fixed rhyme scheme, allowing flexible, conversational phrasing", "the poem is written entirely in rhyming couplets", "the poem follows a strict haiku structure"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem is written in free verse, without a fixed rhyme scheme or strict metre, allowing for flexible, conversational phrasing that suits its reflective, exploratory tone.", "hint": "Look for whether the line endings follow a consistent, predictable rhyme pattern, or move more freely and conversationally."}, {"id": "sde104016", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Author's Purpose", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Read the same poem.\n\nWhich best describes the overall theme explored across this poem?", "options": ["the practical steps involved in fixing household objects", "the mysterious, intangible ways a person's influence can persist in another's body and habits, beyond direct teaching or material inheritance", "the importance of taking family photographs", "a factual biography of the speaker's grandfather"], "answer": 1, "exp": "The poem explores the mysterious, intangible ways a person's influence might persist in another's unconscious gestures and habits, distinct from direct teaching or material inheritance.", "hint": "Think about what idea the poem keeps returning to and exploring from different angles throughout."}, {"id": "sde104017", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Poetry Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "What is a 'volta' in a sonnet?", "options": ["the title of the poem", "a turn or shift in argument, tone, or perspective, typically occurring partway through the poem", "the final word of the poem", "a type of rhyme scheme found only in haiku"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A volta is a turn or shift in argument, tone, or perspective within a sonnet, typically occurring around the eighth or ninth line.", "hint": "Think about a noticeable change of direction partway through a poem's argument or mood."}, {"id": "sde104018", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Poetry Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "What is 'caesura' in poetry?", "options": ["a strong pause or break occurring within a line of poetry, often marked by punctuation", "the very last line of a poem", "a type of rhyme scheme", "a poem with no title"], "answer": 0, "exp": "A caesura is a strong pause or break occurring within a line of poetry, often created by punctuation, which can affect the poem's rhythm and emphasis.", "hint": "Think about a pause that happens in the MIDDLE of a line, not just at the end."}, {"id": "sde104019", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices — Narrative Techniques", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "What does it mean for a poem to use 'free indirect discourse'?", "options": ["a technique blending a character's inner thoughts with the narrator's voice, without using direct quotation", "a poem written entirely in dialogue", "a poem with no punctuation at all", "a strict, traditional poetic form with fourteen lines"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Free indirect discourse blends a character's inner thoughts or speech with the narrator's voice, without using direct quotation marks, creating a subtle blending of perspectives.", "hint": "Think about a technique where you're not sure if you're hearing the narrator or the character's actual thoughts."}, {"id": "sde104020", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Which best describes 'anaphora' as a literary device?", "options": ["the repetition of a word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses or lines", "a single use of alliteration", "a type of question that doesn't expect an answer", "the use of footnotes in formal writing"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Anaphora is the repetition of a word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses or lines, often used for emphasis or rhythmic effect.", "hint": "Think about repeating the same words to START several lines or sentences in a row."}, {"id": "sde104021", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Poetry Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Which best describes 'enjambment' and its typical effect on a poem's pacing?", "options": ["it always slows a poem down dramatically", "it allows a sentence or phrase to continue onto the next line without a pause, which can create a sense of momentum or urgency", "it has no real effect on pacing", "it only occurs in poems with strict rhyme schemes"], "answer": 1, "exp": "Enjambment allows a sentence or phrase to continue onto the next line without a pause, which can create a sense of momentum, urgency, or natural, conversational flow.", "hint": "Think about how NOT pausing at the end of a line might affect how quickly a poem feels like it's moving."}, {"id": "sde104022", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Which best describes a 'conceit' in literary terms, particularly in poetry?", "options": ["a character's excessive pride", "an extended, often elaborate metaphor that structures a significant portion of a poem or piece of writing", "a brief, one-line simile", "a type of formal apology"], "answer": 1, "exp": "A conceit is an extended, often elaborate metaphor that structures a significant portion of a poem, exploring a comparison in depth rather than mentioning it briefly.", "hint": "Think about a metaphor that isn't just mentioned once, but developed and explored throughout much of the piece."}, {"id": "sde104023", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Poetry Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Which best describes 'consonance' as a sound device in poetry?", "options": ["the repetition of consonant sounds, often within or at the end of words, not necessarily at the start", "the repetition of vowel sounds only", "a strict rhyme scheme used in every stanza", "the complete absence of any sound repetition"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Consonance is the repetition of consonant sounds, often within or at the end of words, distinct from alliteration (which specifically repeats sounds at the START of words).", "hint": "Think about repeated consonant sounds that can appear anywhere in nearby words, not just at the beginning."}, {"id": "sde104024", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Poetry Terms", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Which best describes 'assonance' as a sound device in poetry?", "options": ["the repetition of vowel sounds within nearby words", "the repetition of consonant sounds at the start of words", "a type of strict rhyme scheme", "the complete absence of rhythm"], "answer": 0, "exp": "Assonance is the repetition of vowel sounds within nearby words, which can create internal rhyme-like effects without true rhyme.", "hint": "Think about repeated vowel sounds appearing within nearby words, rather than consonant sounds."}, {"id": "sde104025", "state": "AU", "section": "sec_english", "grade": "10", "topic": "Literary Devices", "difficulty": "hard", "style": "standard", "paper": "G10-E4", "q": "Which best describes the effect of an 'extended metaphor' that runs throughout an entire poem, such as comparing memory to a physical inheritance?", "options": ["it creates a single, isolated comparison with no further development", "it builds a sustained, layered comparison that deepens as the poem progresses, allowing for more nuanced exploration of the central idea", "it has no real effect on a poem's meaning", "it can only be used in very short poems"], "answer": 1, "exp": "An extended metaphor builds a sustained, layered comparison across a poem, allowing the writer to explore different facets and nuances of the central idea as it develops.", "hint": "Think about how returning to and developing the same comparison repeatedly might add depth, compared to a single brief mention."}];